name: A-Skips
desc:
-Starting Position:
Begin in a standing position with arms hanging naturally and upper body straight.

-Action:
Lift one thigh with the calf perpendicular to the thigh, hooking the toes while lifting the opposite arm until the thigh is parallel to the floor. As you lift your leg the opposite foot does a skip with the help of calf elasticity.
Actively press down right below the ball of the foot until the forefoot touches the ground. After touching the ground, tap the ground with the help of calf elasticity and then switch legs and hands to drive the body forward.

Tips:
Keep your core tight, keep your torso straight and maintain torso stability.
Quickly leave the ground, reduce the time of touching the ground, ensure that the movement is fast and powerful, feel the elasticity of the lower limbs.
Pay attention to the coordination of hands and feet.
Touch the ground with the forefoot.

name: Alternate Heel Touchers
desc:
Starting Position:
Lie on your back, keep your knees bent, arms at the sides, and keep your back and feet flat on the mat.

Action:
Use the strength of the waist and abdomen to reach for your ankles, alternating arms in a fluid rhythym.

Tip:
In the process of shaking the upper body, only the waist and abdomen should be paid attention to.

name: Archer
desc:
Starting Position:
Stand with a dumbbell in each hand on each side of your body, keeping your body straight.

Action:
Bring your arms up to shoulder height, put your fists together across your chest, keep your elbows straight, keep one arm straight, and bring the other arm back to your armpits in a bow pose.Alternate sides and repeat until recommended.

Tip:
Improve the quality of the movement, and keep both arms at shoulder height throughout the movement.

name: Archer Pull-Up
desc:
-Starting Position:
Hold the bar squarely in both hands with a grip slightly wider than shoulder width and palms facing forward. The body hangs naturally, the feet can be crossed or bent at the knees, and the core is tightened to avoid body sway.

-Action:
Using the back muscles on one side, pull the shoulder of the same side upward and inward, driving the body closer to the bar on that side. Keep your elbow close to your body during the process.
While pulling up, the body naturally twists to the side of force generation, so that the opposite side of the body is as far away from the crossbar as possible, forming a posture similar to that of an archer drawing a bow. The body should remain stable at this point without excessive swaying or imbalance.
Keep the chest of the power side as close to the crossbar as possible, and pause slightly at the highest point.

-Tip:
Exhale as you pull up and inhale as you lower down.
Use the contraction force of your back muscles to pull your body up, rather than relying solely on arm strength.

name: Arnold Press
desc:
-Starting Position:
Standing or sitting position. Keep your torso slightly back and core tight to keep your torso stable.
Grasp dumbbells with both hands, palms facing back, with the dumbbells located on either side of the shoulders at roughly shoulder height.

-Action:
To begin the movement, push your arms upward while slowly rotating your wrists so that your palms turn forward as the dumbbells reach their highest point. Keep an even, steady pace throughout the upward push, using shoulder and arm strength to push the dumbbells up.
Pause briefly when your arms are straight and your palms are forward. Slowly lower the dumbbells, rotating your wrists so that your palms face backward during the process.

-Tip:
Exhale as you push up and inhale as you lower down.
Stop training when you experience discomfort.
Keep your body stable and do not sway.

name: B-Skips
desc:
-Starting Position:
Begin in a standing position with arms hanging naturally and upper body straight.

-Action:
Lift one thigh with the calf perpendicular to the thigh, hooking the toes while lifting the opposite arm until the thigh is parallel to the floor. As you lift your leg the opposite foot does a pad step with the help of calf elasticity.
Extend the knee and press the foot down in front of you until the forefoot touches the ground. After touching the ground, tap the ground with the elasticity of the calf and then switch legs and hands to drive the body forward.

Tips:
Keep your core tight, keep your torso straight, and maintain torso stability.
Quickly leave the ground, reduce the time of touching the ground, ensure that the movement is fast and powerful, feel the elasticity of the lower limbs.
Pay attention to the coordination of hands and feet.
Touch the ground with the forefoot.

name: Back And Forth Step
desc:
Starting Position:
Stand still and let your arms drop.

Action:
Alternate your feet back and forth. Bend your knees slightly during the process. Keep the rhythm.

Tip:
Keep your balance and pace.

name: Back Extensions
desc:
Starting Position:
Lie on your stomach on the back extender with your ankle against the pad and adjust the top pad so that your upper thighs can lean on the pad and your waist is unrestrained when bending.
Keep your body straight with your arms crossed in front of your chest or behind your head.

Action:
Slowly bend forward, pressing as hard as you can until you can't, keeping your back straight and exhaling as you do so.After a short pause, use the strength of your lower back to slowly lift your body back to the Starting Position while inhaling.

Tips:
Keep your balance during the exercise and keep your back unbent.

name: Back Stretch
desc:
-Starting Position:
Kneel with your hips sitting on your heels.

-Action:
Lie forward with your arms shoulder-width apart and press your body and down as far as you can, feeling the stretch in your upper back.
Hold at maximum extent for a while.

-Tips:
Don't hold your breath, keep your breathing rhythm.
Stop training if you experience discomfort.

name: Backward Ball Throw
desc:
Starting Position:
Hold a medicine ball in both hands, half squat, knees bent, feet slightly wider than shoulders.Lean forward, hips back, back and waist straight, and place the pill in the crotch.

Action:
Stretch your hips forward and straighten your legs to stand up.Throw the ball as far back as possible from the front of the body through the top of the head.

Tips:
Single training can be carried out with your back to the wall.

name: Balanced Kick Back
desc:
Starting Position:
Support your body with one leg, knees slightly bent, upper body back parallel to the floor, and the other leg straight back to keep your body flat.

Action:
Lift the upper body with force, while holding the legs straight, swing the back legs forward and bend the knees until the thighs are parallel to the ground in the lunge position.After a short pause, slowly return to the original position and repeat until the recommended number of times.

Tip:
Keep your balance during the exercise.

name: Banded Ankle Eversion
desc:
-Starting Position:
Sit in a seated position with your feet open and shoulder-width apart. Place elastic loops over the insteps of your feet. Point your toes forward.

-Actions:
Drive the toes outward with ankle power. Reach maximum amplitude and slowly return to the starting position.

-Tip:
Exhale on external rotation and inhale on return.
Stop training if you experience discomfort.
Adjust the amount of resistance according to the elasticity of different elastic bands.

name: Banded Ankle Inversion
desc:
-Starting Position:
Sit in a seated position with your feet open and shoulder width apart. Place one end of the elastic loop over the instep of your foot and secure the other end away from your foot. Point your toes forward.

-Actions:
Drive the toes inward with ankle power. Reach maximum amplitude and slowly return to the starting position.

-Tip:
Exhale on internal rotation and inhale on return.
Stop training if you experience discomfort.
Adjust the amount of resistance according to the elasticity of different elastic bands.

name: Banded Hip Abduction
desc:
-Starting Position:
Standing with your legs together, place elastic loops around your ankles. Cross your arms or hold on to a stable place and tighten your core to keep your body steady.

-Action:
Lift one leg to the side, keeping it straight, until it is at its maximum extension. Slowly return to the starting position.

-Tip:
Exhale as you lift your leg and inhale as you return.
Stop training if you experience discomfort.
Adjust the amount of resistance according to the elasticity of different elastic bands or you can fix the band at knee height.

name: Banded Hip Extension
desc:
-Starting Position:
Standing with your legs together, place elastic loops around your ankles. Cross your arms or hold on to a stable place and tighten your core to keep your body steady.

-Action:
Kick one leg out to the back, keeping it straight, until it is at its maximum amplitude. Slowly return to the starting position.

-Tip:
Exhale as you kick and inhale as you return.
Stop training if you experience discomfort.
Adjust the amount of resistance according to the elasticity of different elastic bands, which can also be fixed at knee height.

name: Banded Hip flexion
desc:
-Starting Position:
Standing with your legs together, place elastic loops around your ankles. Cross your arms or hold on to a stable place and tighten your core to keep your body steady.

-Action:
Lift one leg in front of you and keep it straight until it is at its maximum extension. Slowly return to the starting position.

-Tip:
Exhale as you lift your leg and inhale as you return.
Stop training if you experience discomfort.
Adjust the amount of resistance according to the elasticity of different elastic bands, which can also be fixed at knee height.

name: Banded Kneeling Hip Extensions
desc:
-Starting Position:
Kneeling position with hips near heels. The elastic band is secured at a height near the hip on one side and the other is placed over the hip to maintain some tension.

-Action:
Push your hips forward and lift your hips until your thighs are in line with your torso. Sit backward and return to the starting position.

-Cue:
Exhale as you lift your hips and inhale as you return.
Stop training when you experience discomfort.
Adjust the amount of resistance according to the elasticity of different elastic bands.

name: Banded Press
desc:
-Starting Position:
In a seated position, secure the center of the elastic band under your body and hold it in your hands at both sides. Keep your upper arms at an angle to your torso, forearms perpendicular to the floor and elbows slightly forward. Lean your torso back slightly.

-Action:
Push your hands upward with shoulder force until your arms are straight. Slowly return to the starting position.

-Tips:
Exhale as you push up and inhale as you return.
Stop the workout if you experience discomfort.
Adjust the amount of resistance according to the elasticity of different elastic bands.

name: Banded Shoulder external rotation
desc:
-Starting Position:
Stand in a standing position, legs apart, shoulder-width apart. Both axes are close to the sides of the torso, the forearms are perpendicular to the upper arms, and the hands are shoulder-width apart, palms facing upwards holding the elastic band, which is kept under some tension.

-Action:
Using the upper arm as an axis, open the hands to the outside. The position of the elbow does not change during the movement. Slowly return to the starting position after reaching the maximum amplitude.

-Tips:
Exhale as you open and inhale as you return.
Stop training if you experience discomfort.
Adjust the resistance according to the elasticity of different elastic bands.

name: Barbell Front Raise
desc:
-Starting Position:
Feet apart, shoulder-width apart, lean forward slightly, knees slightly bent, keep body stable.
Arms hang naturally and hold the barbell bar in both hands with a slightly wider than shoulder-width grip.

-Action:
With arms straight, lift the barbell forward on the axis of the shoulder joint. Once the upper arms are nearly parallel to the floor, pause briefly and slowly lower back to the starting position.

-Tip:
Exhale as you lift and inhale as you lower.
Stop training if you experience discomfort.
Stabilize the body without swaying and avoid borrowing from the lower extremities.

name: Barbell Good Morning
desc:
-Starting Position:
Feet apart, shoulder-width apart, knees slightly bent. Place a barbell on your obliques and hold the bar with both hands for immobilization. Keep your back straight, tuck in your stomach and chest, and distribute your body weight evenly over your feet.

-Action:
Slowly lean forward on the axis of your hips. Keep your back straight during the dip. At the same time, push your hips back until your torso is nearly parallel to the floor. Push your hips forward and return to the starting position.

-Tip:
Inhale on the dip and exhale on the return.
Determine the range of motion based on flexibility and stop training when you experience discomfort.

name: Barbell Lying Tricep Extensions
desc:
Starting Position:
Lie down on your back with your knees bent and feet planted on the floor. Hold a E-Z Barwith your arms reaching toward the ceiling at shoulder height. 

Action:
Slowly bend at the elbows to bring th weight down to above your forehead. Pause, then, slowly bring the weights back overhead. 

Tips:
Keep your upper arms still throughout.

name: Barbell Plate Halo
desc:
-Starting Position:
Keep your feet shoulder-width apart and your knees slightly bent to keep your body stable. Hold the edge of the barbell piece with both hands in front of your chest.

-Action:
Using your shoulder joints as an axis, slowly begin circling the barbell piece from the side of your head, allowing the piece to follow a circular trajectory around your head.

-Tip:
Stop training when you experience discomfort.
Choose the right weight for the barbell piece.
Maintain stability of the head, torso and lower extremities; do not wobble.

name: Barbell Pullover
desc:
Starting Position:
Lie on your back on the bench, holding the barbell in the palms of your hands, elbows bent and arms perpendicular to the floor.

Action:
Bend your elbows so that the barbell will gradually sink with the palms of your hands toward the head until your arms are parallel to the floor. After a brief pause, slowly lift the barbell until it returns to its Starting Position using the latissimus dorsimus and pectoralis major muscles.

Tips:
Don't use too much weight and feel your back muscles stretch when you exercise.

name: Barbell Row
desc:
Starting Position:
Keep standing and reach down in order to hold a barbell with both hands (knees slightly bent).

Action:
Lift the barbell straight up without moving your back, knees or hips and lower it back after a short pause.

Tips:
Try to keep your back straight throughout. Only the arms should move.

name: Barbell Shrugs
desc:
Starting Position:
Keep standing and hold the barbell down in front of your thighs, arms extended and palms facing back.

Action:
Raise the barbell by raising your shoulders straight up and lower it slowly back down after a short pause.

Tips:
Keep your arms extended throughout.

name: Barbell Stiff-Leg Deadlift
desc:
-Starting Position:
Standing with feet shoulder-width apart, knees slightly bent, barbell resting against the front of the thighs, torso straight. Grip your hands shoulder-width apart.

-Action:
Keeping your back straight, bend at the hips and bend down, lower the barbell along your thighs to just below your knees and feel the hamstring stretch.
Contract your glutes and the back of your thighs and extend your hips to pull the barbell up.

-Tip:
Exhale as you pull up and inhale as you lower down.
Tighten your core and avoid bending your back.
Forward and reverse grips (one hand forward and one hand reverse) may be used to enhance stability.

name: Battle Rope Alternating Waves
desc:
-Starting Position:
Open your feet shoulder-width or slightly wider.
Keep your body slightly leaning forward, sit your hips back and keep your back straight.
Hold one end of the battle rope in each hand with your arms hanging down naturally.

-Action:
Simultaneously use both hands to generate power, bending your arms until the battle rope swings from side to side parallel to the ground, creating a continuous wave shape.
The power comes from the coordinated movement of the entire body, not just the wrist swing.
Strive to synchronize the waves to reach the other end of the battle rope.

-Tip:
Engage core throughout to stabilize the body, preventing swaying with rope movement.
Drive power through entire arms - avoid isolated wrist motion.
Select rope weight and oscillation speed according to individual capability.
Maintain rhythmic breathing patterns with controlled exhalation during exertion.

name: Battle Rope Double Waves
desc:
-Starting Position:
Open your feet shoulder-width or slightly wider.
Keep your body slightly leaning forward, sit your hips back and keep your back straight.
Hold one end of the battle rope in each hand with your arms hanging down naturally.

-Action:
Swing your hands upward vigorously so that the battle ropes form a straight line to about shoulder height.
Then quickly swing the battle rope downward so that it is parallel to the ground and return both hands to the initial position.
Repeat the above movements, maintaining a continuous and rapid swing to form a continuous up and down swing, the movements need to be consistent and rhythmic.

-Tips:
During the movement, the core is tightened to stabilize the body, avoiding the body from swinging up and down with the fluctuation of the rope.
Avoid swinging movements through the wrist alone, but apply power through the entire arm.
Choose the weight of the rope and the speed of the swing according to your ability.
Control your breathing and maintain an even breathing rate.

name: Battle Rope In-and-Out Waves
desc:
-Starting Position:
Open your feet shoulder-width or slightly wider.
Keep your body slightly leaning forward, sit your hips back and keep your back straight.
Hold one end of the battle rope in each hand with your arms hanging down naturally.

-Action:
Spread arms outward to swing the rope out, then move inward bringing hands close to swing the rope in. Continuous motion creates wave patterns.
Power generates from full-body coordination, not just wrist movement.
Strive for synchronized wave arrival at both ends of the battle rope.

-Tip:
During the movement, the core is tightened to stabilize the body and to avoid the body bobbing up and down with the wave of the rope.
Avoid making swinging motions only through the wrist, but apply power through the entire arm.
Choose the weight of the rope and the speed of the swing according to your ability.
Control your breathing and maintain an even breathing rate.

name: Battle Rope Slams
desc:
-Starting Position:
Open your feet shoulder-width or slightly wider.
Keep your body slightly leaning forward, sit your hips back and keep your back straight.
Hold one end of the battle rope in each hand with your arms hanging down naturally.

-Action:
Using the strength of your arms and shoulders, quickly lift the battle rope upward from the sides of your body and then fling it downward with force to form a wave-like shape. Swing as wide and fast as possible to fully stimulate the muscles of the upper limbs.

-Tip:
Avoid making the swinging motion only through the wrist, but apply power through the whole arm.
Choose the weight of the rope and the speed of the swings according to your ability.
Control your breathing and maintain an even breathing rate.

name: Battle Ropes
desc:
Starting Position:
Stand in front of the rope, holding the end of a rope in each hand, with your arms at your side, your body bent slightly, your weight lowered, your feet a certain distance apart, and your horse in place.

Action:
Quickly raise one arm above the shoulder level, as quickly as you can, returning the arm to its original Position, then raise the other arm and repeat.Continue to alternate your left and right arms, swinging the rope up and down as fast as you can and as many times as possible in the shortest amount of time.

Tips:
Balance your body and use the strength of the rest of your body to stabilize yourself.

name: Behind the Neck Press
desc:
-Starting Position:
Sit in a seated position, maintaining postural stability through foot, hip, and back contact with the chair. The torso is straight and the barbell bar is held in the hands, choosing the appropriate grip distance, with the lower arms close to perpendicular to the floor and the bar held with the palms facing forward. The barbell bar is located behind the head.

-Action:
Power up to push the barbell bar upward. Pause briefly with arms straight.
Power up to control speed and slowly return to the starting position.

-Tip:
Exhale on the upward thrust and exhale on the return.
You can choose to train in a standing position, adjusting the height of the barbell bar, feet apart, shoulder-width apart, keeping your body stable and your upper body movement points in unison.
This movement requires good shoulder joint mobility, and stop training when you feel discomfort during the movement.

name: Behind the Neck Pulldowns
desc:
-Starting Position:
Sit on the seat of the pulldown trainer and stabilize your lower extremities by placing your feet firmly on the ground.
Keep your back naturally straight and tighten your core to stabilize your body. Slightly lower and extend your shoulders back, and lean your head and torso slightly forward.
Hold the pull-up bar with your hands at shoulder-width distance, palms facing forward.

-Action:
Sink your shoulder blades and fire your latissimus dorsi muscles to drive your upper arms downward, slowly pulling the pull-up bar down along the back of your head to ear height.
After a brief pause at the lowest point, slowly and in a controlled manner, extend your arms upward to return to the starting position.

-Tip:
Exhale on the pull down and inhale on the return.
Choose the right weight.
Control the speed and amplitude of the pull down to avoid injury. Stop this movement if you feel shoulder or neck discomfort during the exercise.

name: Bench Dips
desc:
Starting Position:
Sit with your back to the bench and your hands on the edge of the bench behind you.

Action:
Chest, arms, shoulders and neck will force the body up at the same time, slowly bend the elbow, make the body sink, until the hips almost touch the ground, chest, arms, shoulders and neck will force the body back up at the same time, repeat to the recommended times.

Tip:
Pay attention to the rhythm and breathing during the exercise.

name: Bench Press
desc:
Starting Position:
Sit on the 45 degree bench Position and grasp the handles with your palms facing forward.

Action:
Push the handles forward and slightly upwards by straightening your arms and allow them to slowly return after a short pause.

Tips:
Breathe out while pushing forward and breathe in while returning to Starting Position.

name: Bench Press With Bands
desc:
Starting Position:
Pass a stretch strip under the bench, close to the side of the head, around the chest.Lie on your back on the bench with your chest out and stomach in, keeping your back straight.Hold one side of the elastic band in each hand and extend the arm up to shoulder width.

Action:
Then slowly lower your hands and bend your arms until your chest is stretched to the limit.Inhale as you descend.After a brief pause at the bottom, lift your arms up quickly with chest force until they are naturally straight.Exhale as you lift.

Tips:
In the process of two-handed descent, the force should not be fully discharged, and the force should be slowly reduced to improve the effectiveness of training.

name: Bent-over Lateral Raise
desc:
Starting Position:
Lie prone on the bench and grab two dumbbells underneath you, elbows at 90 degree angles.

Action:
Raise the dumbbells to the sides without moving your upper arms and lower them back after a short pause.

Tips:
Breathe out while raising the dumbbells and breathe in while lowering them back.

name: Bicep Curl-Machine
desc:
-Starting Position:
Sit in a seated position, maintaining postural stability through foot, hip, chest, and arm contact with the apparatus. Hold the handles of the apparatus with both hands.

-Action:
With two hairs, bend your elbows to drive the handles upward. Pause briefly after reaching maximum amplitude.
Generate power to control speed and slowly return to the starting position.

-Tip:
Exhale as you bend and exhale as you return.
Stop training if you feel discomfort during the movement.

name: Bicep Stretch
desc:
-Starting Position:
Keep one arm straight with the palm of the hand against the wall.

-Action:
Slowly turn your body in the opposite direction (away from the side of your arm), keeping your arm straight and pressed against the wall.
Feel the stretch in your biceps and avoid shrugging or arching your back.

-Tip:
If you have shoulder or elbow discomfort, adjust the height of your hand or reduce your body rotation.

name: Biceps Curls With Bands
desc:
Starting Position:
Keep your body in a standing Position with your feet shoulder-width apart and your arms hanging down.Step on the elastic belt and hold the handle in your hand.

Action:
Fix the elbow on both sides of the waist ribs, grasp the elastic band handle with both hands in reverse, with the elbow as the axis, use the strength of the big arm to pull up the elastic band, pull to the part that cannot rise after a short stay, slowly down.

Tips:
Keep your back and waist straight and steady during practice.

name: Bicycle Crunches
desc:
Starting Position:
Sit on the floor, lean back to rest on your forearms, bend your hips and extend one leg 45 degrees from the ground.

Action:
While you push one leg out until it is stretched forward, bring the other one back so that you are cycling through the air.

Tips:
Try to keep your back straight throughout.

name: Bird Dog
desc:
Starting Position:
Start on all fours. Stretch your right arm out in front of you, then extend your left leg behind you. This should resemble a bird-dog, pointing out the birds.

Action:
While holding the position, bring your extended limbs back to the starting position, then extend out again and repeat.

Tip:
Focus on from by keeping your neck in line with your spine, your hips level and the extended limbs straight.

name: Bird-Dog Balance
desc:
-Starting Position:
Stand side-by-side, side planks, eyes forward.
Lift one side foot forward, toes straight, while keeping your arms up to keep your body balanced.

-Actions:
The stepped out leg drops, driving the body forward, and the front foot lands on the ground and stands firm. Lift the back side leg back while opening both arms to the sides until the torso and back side leg are parallel to the ground. Pause briefly to maintain balance.
Return to standing position.

-Tip:
Coordinate the muscles of the legs and core to maintain balance and avoid large wobbles.

name: Bosu Ball Crunches
desc:
Starting Position:
Lay on the bosu ball (flat side down) parralel to the ground placing your hands behind your head with your knees bent, feet planted on the floor. 

Action:
Crunch up iinto a sit up position. Hold the position for a second before slowly retratcing to the starting position. 

Tips:
Start slow as handling the balance of the bosu ball can be challenging.

name: Bosu Ball High Knee Lunge
desc:
-Starting Position:
Ball face down.
Lower limbs are in a reverse lunge position. The front foot is placed in the center of the platform above the bosu ball with the opposite hand in front.
Tighten the core and straighten the torso.

-Action:
Register and extend the knee and hip of the front side leg to bring the body upright. Simultaneously lift the knee of the back side leg up
until the thigh is slightly above horizontal.
Coordinate your core, hips and lower body muscles to maintain balance and minimize swaying during the movement.

Tip:
Assist the movement by swinging your arms.
Repeat the same side of the leg as one set several times, or alternate bilaterally.
The difficulty of the movement can be reduced by turning the ball face up.
Exhale on the way up and inhale on the way down.

name: Bosu Ball Push-Ups
desc:
Starting Position:
Place a BOSU on the floor, platform side up. Adopt a push up Position with hands in a medium grip Position on top of the BOSU platform.

Action:
Push yourself up by extending your arms and lower yourself back down after a short pause.

Tips:
Breathe out while pushing yourself up and breathe in while lowering yourself down.

name: Bosu Ball Single Leg Hold
desc:
-Starting Position:
Ball face down.
Standing on a platform, support your body with one leg, bend your other leg at the knee to bring your foot off the platform, and keep your arms open to keep your body balanced.

-Action:
Stand on one leg on a bosu ball for a certain amount of time.
Coordinate the muscles of the core, hips, and lower extremities to maintain balance and minimize body sway during the execution of the movement.

-Tips:
You can decrease the difficulty of the movement by turning the ball face up.
You can increase the difficulty of the movement by clasping your hands in front of your chest.

name: Bosu Ball Single-Leg Deadlift
desc:
-Starting position:
Ball face down.
Stand on a platform and balance by supporting your body on one leg with a slight bend in the knee, leaning your upper body forward parallel to the ground and straightening the other leg back.

-Action:
Lift your torso up with all your might while straightening your supporting leg, swinging your back leg forward and returning to a standing position. After a short pause slowly return to the original position and repeat the movement until the recommended number of repetitions.
Coordinate your core, hips and lower body muscles to maintain balance and minimize swaying.

Tip:
You can reduce the difficulty of the movement by turning the ball face up.
Exhale on the way up and inhale on the way down.

name: Bosu Ball Squats
desc:
Starting Position:
Stand on one side of the ball and place the ball flat up with your feet shoulder-width apart.Keep your waist and back straight with your head facing straight ahead.

Action:
Bend your knees and hips and lower your body, keeping your knees, feet and hips together.Squat as deep as your flexibility allows.Don't sag your knees and don't bend your thoracic vertebra.After a short pause in the Position where the squat is not possible, extend your knees and hips and return to the Starting Position.

Tips:
During the practice, it is important to master the balance of the wave ball, and the overall movement is similar to the squat.

name: Bounce A Boat
desc:
Starting Position:
Keep your upper body straight, hold the elastic band tightly with one arm, bend your elbows, keep your waist straight, and open your legs forward and backward to stabilize the center of gravity.

Action:
Pull the elastic band to one side of your body, and move your arms back and forth naturally according to the rhythm. At the same time, your legs can jump back and forth alternately according to the rhythm.Repeat to recommended times.

Tip:
Require light and flexible landing;Expiratory row after pulling, request acceleration burst;Swing your arms in harmony with nature.

Practical Application:
Diagonal force control can improve the integration ability of the body and improve the movement efficiency of running.

name: Bounce A Boat With A Lunge
desc:
Starting Position:
Keep your upper body straight, hold the elastic band tightly with one arm, bend your elbows, keep your waist straight, and open your legs forward and backward to stabilize the center of gravity.

Action:
Pull the elastic band to one side of your body, swing your arms back and forth naturally according to the rhythm, and complete the lunge with your legs in rhythm.Repeat to recommended times.

Tip:
Complete the unilateral lunge jump training, pay attention to the fall control.

Practical Application:
Lower limb strength centrifugal training, improve the landing control of running and downhill, reduce landing impact.

name: Box Jumps
desc:
Starting Position:
Stand in front of a box with feet shoulder width apart, with legs slightly bent.

Action:
Use your arms and jump on to the box. Land softly with feet straight ahead and knees over feet. Step down and repeat as quickly as can be controlled.

Tips:
Use a box or step that is a suitable height for your fitness level.

name: Box Squat
desc:
-Starting Position:
Choose a box of appropriate height to place behind you. Keep your feet shoulder-width apart.
Keep your back naturally straight and tuck in your stomach and chest.

-Action:
Squat down, bending your knees and hips, with your knees pointing in the same direction as your toes. Pause briefly after sitting your hips back and lightly touching the box. Then pedal and extend the lower leg to slowly return to the starting position.

-Tip:
Inhale as you squat and exhale as you rise.
Stop training when you experience discomfort.
Tighten your core throughout to avoid swaying your body.
You can carry a barbell on your back or hold a dumbbell kettlebell for weight training.

name: Box Step Up Knee Drive
desc:
-Starting Position:
Stand in front of a jump box or step with your arms hanging down naturally.

-Action:
Lift one leg, thigh as high as possible, calf hanging down naturally. Quickly step onto the step, stomping and extending your lower leg to drive your body up the step. Simultaneously lift the other leg up in a smooth motion until the thigh is parallel to the floor. Maintain balance. Then return to the bottom of the step.

Tip:
Coordinate arm swings to maintain balance.
Explosive strength training move that requires a quick ascent of the steps.
Weights can be used to increase the difficulty of the movement.

name: Box Step-Ups
desc:
Starting Position:
Keep standing on the bench.

Action:
Lift one foot onto the bench, balance your legs, lift your body until your feet are together, then slowly return to your original position after a short pause. Repeat for the recommended number of times.

Tip:
Pay attention to the power position to improve the effectiveness of training.

name: Bridge
desc:
Starting Position:
Lie on the floor, knees at 90 degree angles and place your hands flat on the floor, arms extended.

Action:
Raise your buttocks from the floor as high as you comfortably can and lower it back down after a short pause.

Tips:
Your feet and hands should not move throughout.

name: Bridging Psoas March
overview: start with feet on a box with legs fully extended and a small resistance band around the feet. Lift hips off the ground and maintains this hip height while one leg pulls into chest.

name: Burpees
desc:
Starting Position:
Keep standing with feet hip width apart and feet pointing straight ahead.

Action:
Begin to squat, placing your palms on the floor between your feet. Put your weight on your hands and jump your feet back to a push-up Position. Jump your feet forwards and stand up.

Tips:
Squat down, do not bend down. Add a push up to increase the difficulty.

name: C-Skips
desc:
-Starting Position:
Begin in a standing position with arms hanging naturally and upper body straight.

-Action:
Lift one thigh with the calf perpendicular to the thigh, hooking the toes while lifting the opposite arm until the thigh is parallel to the floor. As you lift your leg the opposite foot does a pad step with the help of calf elasticity.
The active foot presses down right under the ball of the foot until the forefoot touches the ground. After touching the ground the opposite foot pads while lifting the thigh to the outside of the body with the calf perpendicular to the thigh until the thigh is parallel to the ground and then presses down on the ball of the foot.
Tap the ground after the forefoot touches the ground, and switch legs and hands to drive the body forward.

Tips:
Keep your core tight, ensure your torso is straight, and maintain torso stability.
Get off the ground quickly, reduce the time of touching the ground, make sure the movement is fast and powerful, and feel the elasticity of the lower limbs.
Pay attention to the coordination of hands and feet.
Touch the ground with the forefoot.

name: Cable Glute Kickbacks
desc:
Starting Position:
Set the pulley to its lowest height and wrap the cable around your ankle.Stand facing the pulley Position and grab the steel column of the machine to support the body.

Action:
Bend the knees and hips slightly, tighten the abdomen, tighten the gluteus maximus, draw an arc behind the kick, then slowly pull the leg back into Position, tightening the cable tension as you do so.

Tips:
Keep your upper body still while you're doing it. Try to move slowly and balance your legs.

name: Cable Lateral Raise
desc:
-Starting Position:
Rope pulley adjusted to ankle height. Stand in the center of the gantry with legs open and shoulder-width apart, knees slightly bent, and hands holding the handles of the ropes on opposite sides, palms facing each other.

-Action:
The middle deltoid bundle powers up to pull up the rope, with the arms on each side held sideways and flat, just until they are parallel to or slightly below the shoulders.
Slowly lower your arms back to the starting position.

-Tip:
Exhale as you pull up and inhale as you lower down.
In addition to bilateral lateral raises, you can also perform unilateral lateral raises. The movement points are similar, with the difference being that you need to immobilize the arm on one side to ensure body stability.
The elbow is slightly bent to minimize stress on the elbow.

name: Cable Pull-Through
desc:
-Starting Position:
The pulley of the rope is in the lowest position. With your back to the apparatus, open your legs slightly wider than shoulder-width apart and slightly bent at the knees. Lean your upper body forward to the extent that your hips and the back of your thighs are tightened. Hold the handles with both hands, palms facing each other, arms straight.

-Action:
Push your hips forward, driving your torso up until your body is upright.
Bend your hips backward and slowly return to the starting position.

-Tip:
Keep your arms straight at all times without actively exerting force.
Inhale as you lower your body and exhale as you pull it up.

name: Cable Reverse Fly
desc:
-Starting Position:
Keep your feet open and shoulder-width apart to keep your body stable.
Raise your arms flat in front of you, slightly below your shoulders, making a small angle between your arms and your torso. Hold the rope handle on the opposite side with the ropes crossed. Keep your arms straight and at shoulder level.

-Action:
A force from the back of the shoulder drives the elbow backward, driving the arm backward and opening it up, keeping the angle of the elbow joint constant during the process.
Arms and body line up to reach maximum amplitude, pause briefly and slowly return to the starting position.

Tips:
Breathe
Exhale as you pull back and inhale as you return
Feel the force at the back of your shoulders.

name: Cable Rotation
desc:
-Starting Position:
The pulley of the rope is at chest height. Turn your body sideways to the pulley, feet apart, shoulder width apart, core tight, knees slightly bent. Keep a distance from the apparatus to ensure that there is tension on the rope at all times.
Shoulders drive the torso towards the apparatus, hands grip the handles and arms are straight.

-Action:
Using the body midline as an axis, keep the lower body still, and with sideways force from the abdomen, rotate the upper body in the direction away from the apparatus, and arc your hands with the rotation of the body.
After reaching maximum amplitude, slowly reverse the rotation and return to the starting position.

Tip:
Exhale as you rotate and inhale as you return.
Power only through the lumbar and abdominal rotator muscle groups, keeping the lower body as stable as possible.

name: Calf Stretch
desc:
-Starting Position:
Stand with feet front and back apart, front leg bent at the knee, back leg straight, heels as close to the ground as possible.

-Action:
Lower your hips and feel the tugging sensation on the back of the rear calf of your back leg.
You can hook the toes of your back foot or raise your hands upward to further stretch the back of your calf.

-Tip:
Don't hold your breath and maintain a breathing rhythm.
Stop training if you experience discomfort.

name: Cardio Kickboxing
desc:
Starting Position:
Maintain a fighting or defensive stance.

Action:
Use the fist, elbow, knee, foot and other parts to attack or defend the target.

Tips:
Pay attention to your center of gravity and your breathing rhythm.

name: Cat-Cow Stretch
desc:
-Starting Position:
Hands and knees on the floor in a four-point support position. Hands are shoulder-width apart, knees are hip-width apart, back remains flat, and abdomen is tightened.

-Actions:
Cow Pose: As you inhale, tilt your pelvis forward, tilt your tailbone up, and extend your lumbar, thoracic, and cervical vertebrae section by section, forming a concave arc of the back.
Cat Pose: Look up to the front or above, chest open, shoulder blades inward, abdomen slightly stretched but core control maintained.
As you exhale, roll backward from the pelvis, arching the lumbar, thoracic, and cervical vertebrae section by section, the back rises like a cat arching its back.
Look down to the abdomen, which tucks in, core activates, and hips tighten slightly.

-Tip:
Move the entire spine and fully extend the low back in a controlled manner.

name: Chest Flys With Bands
desc:
Starting Position:
In a standing Position, place the elastic band around your chest, with your forearms parallel to your body and slightly below your chin.

Action:
Use chest strength to combine your hands to pull the elastic band. After the combination, you can squeeze slightly to improve the training effect, and then slowly return to the Starting Position.

Tips:
In this process, the arms rotate with the shoulders as the axis, the rest of the Position cannot be changed, with the corresponding parts to maintain stability.

name: Chest Press-Machine
desc:
-Starting Position:
Sit in a seated position, maintaining postural stability through contact of the feet, hips, and back with the apparatus. Bend the elbows, angle the upper arms to the body about 60, and hold the handles of the apparatus with both hands.

-Action:
With chest and triple hair force, extend the elbows to push the handles forward. Pause briefly after straightening the arms.
Chest and triple hair force to control speed and slowly return to the starting position.

Tip:
Exhale as you push forward and exhale as you return.
Keeping the upper arm at an angle to the torso reduces stress on the shoulder joint.
Stop training if you feel discomfort during the movement.

name: Chest Stretch
desc:
-Starting Position:
Stand with your feet front and back apart.
Raise one arm against a wall with the upper arm parallel to the floor and the lower arm perpendicular to the floor.

-Action:
Turn your torso and feel the stretch in your chest.

-Tip:
Don't hold your breath and maintain a breathing rhythm.
Stop training if you experience discomfort.

name: Clamshell
desc:
-Starting position:
Side lying position. The side of the body and one leg are in contact with the floor, ensuring stability of the body through the support point. Bend the knee. Place an elastic band around the knee area.

-Action:
Maintain pelvic stability. Using the hip as an axis, the knee of the upper leg opens upwards and both knees move away from each other overcoming resistance. Open to the maximum extent and then slowly return to the initial position. Keep the feet and hips still during the opening of the legs.

Tips:
Inhale when the legs are open and exhale when the legs are closed.
Stop training if you experience discomfort.
Adjust the amount of resistance according to the elasticity of different elastic bands, you can remove the elastic bands to train unloaded.

name: Clapping Push-Up
desc:
-Starting Position:
Hands on the ground, shoulder-width apart or slightly wider than shoulder-width apart. Head, torso and legs in a straight line.

-Action:
Keeping your body stable, slowly bend your elbows to lower your body, keeping your elbows close to your body. Pause briefly when the upper arm is nearly parallel to the ground. Quickly push your body upward, leaving your hands on the ground with a quick high-five in the air, then open your hands to touch the ground to cushion and return to the starting position.
When executing the movement, always keep your core muscles tight and your back straight, without collapsing or puckering your hips. Keep your neck naturally extended and don't tilt or bow your head excessively.

-Tip:
Inhale as you descend and exhale as you push up.
Stop training when experiencing discomfort.
Adjust the range of descent according to flexibility and personal ability.

name: Close Grip Push-Up
desc:
-Starting Position:
Hands on the ground, slightly less than shoulder distance apart. Head, torso and legs in a straight line.

-Action:
Keeping your body stable, slowly bend your elbows to lower your body, keeping your elbows close to your body. Pause briefly when the upper arm is nearly parallel to the ground. Push your body upward to return to the starting position.
When performing the movement, always keep your core muscles tight and your back straight, do not collapse or pucker your hips. Keep your neck naturally extended and don't tilt your head up or down excessively.

-Tip:
Inhale as you descend and exhale as you push up.
Stop training when experiencing discomfort.
Adjust the range of descent according to flexibility and personal ability.

name: Close-Grip Bench Press
desc:
-Starting Position:
Lie on your back on a bench press bench, maintaining a stable position through your feet, hips, back, and head.
Hold the barbell squarely in both hands with a grip no wider than shoulder width and arms straight.

-Action:
Slowly lower the barbell, keeping your upper arms at an angle to your torso, until the barbell is close to your chest.
After a brief pause push the barbell back to the starting position.

-Tip:
Exhale as you push up and inhale as you return.
Stop the workout if you experience discomfort.

name: Close-Grip Dumbbell Bench Press
desc:
-Starting Position:
Lie on your back on a bench press bench, maintaining a stable position through your feet, hips, back, and head.
Hold dumbbells in your hands, palms facing each other, with the dumbbells spaced narrowly enough to touch, arms straight.

-Action:
Slowly lower the dumbbells, making sure they are spaced the same distance apart, until they are close to your chest.
Pause briefly and then power up to push the dumbbells back to the starting position.

-Tip:
Exhale as you push up and inhale as you return.
Stop training if you experience discomfort.

name: Copenhagen Plank
desc:
-Starting Position:
Take a side plank position with the elbow of the supporting hand directly under the shoulder and the other side hand raised or crossed. Rest the inside calf of the supporting leg on the bench, keeping the supporting leg parallel to the floor.

-Action:
The other leg is actively tucked in, as close to the supporting leg as possible. The body needs to be kept in a straight line, avoiding hip flexion or excessive hip jacking, and no lateral flexion at the waist.

name: Crawl On The Ground
desc:
Starting Position:
Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart.

Action
Bend over, touch the ground in front of your feet with your hands, adjust your position and try not to bend your knees.Move your hands forward, keeping your knees straight and your upper body straight, until you are in a push-up ready position. Hold the position briefly and then move your body back and back into a standing position.Repeat to recommended times.

Tip:
Improve the quality of movement, keep the upper body and knees straight, do not move the feet.

name: Crossbody Calf Hug
desc:
-Starting Position:
Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart, keeping your spine naturally straight and your core tight.

-Action:
Lift one leg, bend the knee, and grab the ankle and just below the knee. Pull the bent leg toward your chest and feel the stretch in the outer gluteal muscles.
Switch legs for the exercise.

-Tip:
This can be practiced in place or alternated while marching.
You can also tiptoe up on the toes of your standing leg while stretching to stretch further.

name: Crunch
desc:
Starting Position:
Keep your back position on the mat with your legs together, knees bent, hands flat at your sides.

Action:
While engaging your core slowly lift your upper body elevating both the upper and lower vertebrae from the floor until everything superior to the buttocks is not touching the ground

Tip:
During the exercise focus on engaging your core through the entire motion.

name: Crunch - Legs On Exercise Ball
desc:
Starting Position:
Lie flat on the mat with your legs bent at 90 degrees and your feet on a Swiss ball.Hold your hands at the sides of your head, elbows out.

Action:
Keeping your lower back on the ground, use your lower belly to lift your shoulders and exhale.Until the abdominal muscles contract to the limit.After a brief pause, return slowly to the Starting Position, inhaling.

Tips:
Do not use the strength of other parts of the exercise process, only with the strength of the waist and abdomen.

name: Curtsey Squat
desc:
Starting Position:
Maintain a standing position with your body straight.

Action:
Stand straight with your arms out in front. Pick one leg off the ground and cross it behind your other leg. Slowly lower your body to the ground, until your hips are in a normal squat position. Drive up through your standing leg and repeat on the other side.

Tip:
Pay attention to your balance. Keep your back straight as you rise and fall, moving slowly and effectively.

name: Dead Bug
desc:
-Starting Position:
Lie on your back on the mat with your arms straight up perpendicular to the floor, palms facing each other or fists clenched.
Bend knees and raise legs with thighs perpendicular to the floor, calves parallel to the floor, and knees directly above hips.

-Action:
Slowly lower the opposite arm and leg, with the large arm close to the ear and the leg straightened out to the far side, both close to being parallel to the ground but not on the ground.
Core power drives the limbs back to the starting position.

-Tips:
Inhale as you lower and exhale as you return.
Control the movement to minimize swaying.

name: Deadlifts
desc:
Starting Position:
Crouch down to reach the barbell on the floor and grab it with both hands in a medium-grip Position, arms extended, legs at shoulder width.

Action:
Raise yourself up while keeping your arms extended and slowly lower yourself back down after a short pause.

Tips:
Breathe out while raising yourself and breathe in while lowering yourself back.

name: Deadlifts with Bands
desc:
Starting Position:
Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart, bend over, keep your waist and back straight, keep your shoulder joints in front of your knees, and hold the elastic rope.

Action:
Contract the back of the buttocks and thighs to return the body to an upright Position, keeping the knees slightly bent as you go.

Tips:
Keep your back and waist straight.

name: Decline Bench Press
desc:
Starting Position:
Lie down on your back on the decline bench and grasp the barbell with both hands in a medium-grip Position.

Action:
Push the barbell straight up until your elbows are close to being locked and lower it back slowly after a short pause.

Tips:
Breathe out while pushing the bar and breathe in while lowering it back.

name: Decline Dumbbell Bench Press
desc:
-Starting Position:
Lie on your back on an Incline Bench Press Bench, maintaining a stable position through your feet, hips, back, and head.
Keep your upper arms at an angle to your torso, in contact with the floor, and your forearms perpendicular to the floor, holding dumbbells in your hands.

-Action:
Chest power push the dumbbells upward until the arms are straight. Slowly return to the starting position.

-Tip:
Exhale as you push up and inhale as you return.
Stop the workout if you experience discomfort.

name: Decline Push-Up
desc:
-Starting Position:
Place your feet on a higher platform, such as a stool or box. Hands are braced on the floor, spaced shoulder-width apart or slightly wider than shoulder-width apart. Head, torso and legs are in a straight line.

-Action:
Keeping your body stable, slowly bend your elbows to lower your body, keeping your elbows close to your body. Pause briefly when the upper arm is nearly parallel to the ground. Push your body upward to return to the starting position.
When performing the movement, always keep your core muscles tight and your back straight, do not collapse or pucker your hips. Keep your neck naturally extended and don't tilt your head up or down excessively.

-Tip:
Inhale as you descend and exhale as you push up.
Stop training when experiencing discomfort.
Adjust the range of descent based on flexibility and individual ability.
Increase the difficulty of the movement by increasing the height of the feet and decrease the height to decrease the difficulty.

name: Decline Weighted Crunch
desc:
-Starting Position:
Remain in a supine position on a downward sloping plank with the barbell plates resting on your chest in both hands.

-Actions:
Use your lower back and abdominal strength to lift your upper body, stop briefly to squeeze your abs and then slowly lower your upper body back to its original position, and repeat the movement for the recommended number of reps.

-Tip:
Pay attention to the rhythm of body movement control, barbell piece according to their own actual situation to choose.

name: Diamond Push-Up
desc:
-Starting Position:
With your hands on the ground, touch your thumbs and forefingers to each other to form a diamond-like lozenge shape. Head, torso and legs in a straight line.

-Action:
Keeping your body stable, slowly bend your elbows to lower your body, keeping your elbows close to your body. Pause briefly when the upper arm is nearly parallel to the ground. Push your body upward to return to the starting position.
When performing the movement, always keep your core muscles tight and your back straight, do not collapse or pucker your hips. Keep your neck naturally extended and don't tilt your head up or down excessively.

-Tip:
Inhale as you descend and exhale as you push up.
Stop training when experiencing discomfort.
Adjust the range of descent according to flexibility and personal ability.

name: Donkey Kicks
desc:
-Starting Position:
Hands and knees on the floor in a four-point support position. Keep your hands shoulder-width apart and your knees hip-width apart, keep your back flat and your abdominals tight.

-Actions:
Glute muscles fire to drive one leg back and up, keeping the knee bent (about 90 degrees) until the ball of the foot is pointing toward the ceiling and the knee, hip and upper body are in a straight line.
After a short pause, lower the leg slowly and in a controlled manner to return to the starting position, but without the knee on the ground.

-Tip:
Exhale as you lift and inhale as you lower.
Keep your core stable and avoid collapsing or arching your lower back; the movement should be dominated by the glutes.

name: Dumbbell Bench Press
desc:
-Starting Position:
Lie on your back on a bench press bench, maintaining a stable position through your feet, hips, back, and head.
Keep your upper arms at an angle to your torso, in contact with the floor, and your forearms perpendicular to the floor, holding dumbbells in your hands.

-Action:
Chest power push the dumbbells upward until your arms are straight. Slowly return to the starting position.

-Tip:
Exhale as you push up and inhale as you return.
Stop the workout if you experience discomfort.

name: Dumbbell Biceps Curls
desc:
Starting Position:
Stand up and hold one dumbbell with each hand, one down the side of your body and the other up near your shoulder, palms facing your body.

Action:
Raise one dumbbell toward your shoulder and while slowly lowering it back down after a short pause.

Tips:
Keep your back and upper arms still throughout.

name: Dumbbell Flys
desc:
Starting Position:
Lie down on your back on the bench and grab one dumbbell with each hand at shoulder height, elbows just slightly arched.

Action:
Raise the dumbbells until they are side by side on top of you and slowly lower them back after a short pause.

Tips:
Try to maintain the same angle in your elbows throughout.

name: Dumbbell Good Morning
desc:
-Starting Position:
Feet apart, shoulder-width apart, knees slightly bent. Hold the ends of the dumbbells with both hands and hug them in front of your chest. Keep your back straight, tuck in your stomach and lift your chest, and distribute your body weight evenly over your feet.

-Action:
Slowly bend forward on the axis of your hips. Keep your back straight during the lean. At the same time, push your hips back until your torso is nearly parallel to the floor. Push your hips forward and return to the starting position.

-Tip:
Inhale on the dip and exhale on the return.
Determine the range of motion based on flexibility and stop training when you experience discomfort.

name: Dumbbell Lunges
desc:
Starting Position:
Keep standing up and hold one dumbbell with each hand against the side of your body, palms facing each other.

Action:
Take a wide step forward so that your knee shows a 90 degree angle and slowly bring yourself back up after a short pause. Alternate feet between repetitions.

Tips:
Keep your back straight throughout.

name: Dumbbell Pullover
desc:
Starting Position:
Lie on your back on the bench with your palms on the back of the dumbbell, elbows bent and arms perpendicular to the floor.

Action:
Bend at the elbow and let the dumbbell sink gradually along with the palm toward the head until the arm is parallel to the ground. After a short pause, slowly lift the dumbbell until it returns to the Starting Position using the latissimus dorsius and pectoralis major muscles.

Tips:
Don't use too much weight and feel your back muscles stretch when you exercise.

name: Dumbbell Romanian Deadlift
desc:
-Starting Position:
Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart or slightly narrower, toes facing forward or slightly outward, knees slightly bent.
Hold dumbbells in each hand, naturally hanging down on the front of your thighs with your palms facing your body, keep your back straight and your core tight.

-Action:
Using your hips as an axis, push your hips back and slowly lower the dumbbells along the front of your thighs, close to your calves. Feel the stretch in the hamstrings and glutes.
Return the dumbbells below the knee or close to the mid-calf to the starting position.

-Tip:
Inhale as you lower and exhale as you rise.
Choose range of motion based on flexibility.

name: Dumbbell Row
desc:
Starting Position:
Keep standing and reach down in order to hold two dumbbells with both hands (knees slightly bent).

Action:
Lift the dumbbells straight up while keeping your back still and lower them back after a short pause.

Tips:
Try to keep your back straight throughout. Only the arm should move.

name: Dumbbell Shrugs
desc:
Starting Position:
Keep standing and hold one dumbbell with each hand in front of your thighs, palms facing your body.

Action:
Raise the dumbbells straight up by raising your shoulders and lower them back after a short pause.

Tips:
Keep your arms extended throughout.

name: Dumbbell Side Bends
desc:
Starting Position:
Keep standing and hold a dumbbell with one hand along the side of your body.Rest your other hand gently on your head.

Action:
Lean your upper body to the side that holds the dumbbell and bring it back after a short pause. Complete your set and change sides.

Tips:
Try to keep your back straight throughout.

name: Dumbbell Side Plank Rotations
desc:
-Starting Position:
Remain in a side-lying position, keeping your body straight by propping your elbow on the ground on the near side of your body. Hold a dumbbell on the other side and rotate your torso to place the dumbbell on the floor.

-Action:
Turn your body to the side while opening the arm on the same side to point directly overhead. The core fires to keep the head, torso and legs in a straight line. Then slowly return to the starting position.

-Tip:
Exhale as you rotate and inhale as you return.
This movement is used to improve core stability, so it's important to coordinate the force through the lower back and hips to prevent the body from twisting or swaying during the workout.

name: Dumbbell Snatch
desc:
-Starting Position:
Feet apart, slightly wider than shoulder width, dumbbells placed between feet. Flex your hips, hips back, calves and floor near vertical, and hold the dumbbells in one hand. Keep your core tight and avoid collapsing your back.

Action:
Quickly stomp and extend your ankles, knees, and hips to straighten your body while pulling the dumbbells up. Pull the dumbbells up to shoulder height with an upward explosive force, then turn your elbows to rotate the dumbbells and lift them above your head.
Hold briefly, then slowly return to the starting position.

-Tip:
Inhale on the squat and exhale on the lift.
Stop the workout if you experience discomfort.
Ensure core stabilization, transfer the force upward from the lower body and lift the dumbbells with the help of stirrups and extensions, without active force from the upper body to push upward.
Other tools such as kettlebells can be used to provide weight.

name: Dumbbell Thruster
desc:
-Starting Position:
Feet apart, shoulder-width apart, hold dumbbells on either side of your shoulders with both hands, palms facing inward.

-Action:
Squat: Bend your hips and knees and squat at an even pace, keeping your knees in the same direction as your toes during the squat. Squat until thighs are parallel to the ground or slightly lower.
Upward Push:
Use the power of your legs and hips to quickly pedal up and push your body upward. As your body pushes upward, your arms should quickly push the dumbbells upward until your arms are straight and the dumbbells are above your head. Transfer the power from your legs to your hips and then through your spine to your upper body to provide a strong momentum for pushing the dumbbells up.

-Tip:
Keep your body balanced and stable.
Inhale as you squat and exhale as you push up.
Evenly descend to build strength and push up quickly to release it.
Leg stomps and arm pushes should be coordinated to form a coherent whole, making full use of the explosive power of each joint.

name: Elastic Band Bends Hip And Pulls Back
desc:
Starting Position:
Stand with feet open and knees slightly bent, in a semi-squat position, to stabilize the center of gravity.The waist is bent and the upper body is level with the floor;Extend one arm forward and hold the elastic band tightly. Extend the other arm behind your body.

Action:
Pull the elastic band to the body, and at the same time lift the upper body and slightly back, two arms swing back and forth naturally, the waist from bending to straight, straight knees, so that the whole body into a straight standing posture.Return to original condition after a short stay and repeat to recommended number of times.

Tip:
With the hip joint as the hinge, complete the correct transmission chain of the hip - core - shoulder arm.Improve training effect and maintain a certain rhythm of movement.

Practical Application:
It is a good basic training movement for how to deliver hip during running.It is also helpful to improve the efficiency of swinging arms.

name: Elastic Band Plate Pull-down
desc:
Starting Position:
Maintain a push-up preparation position with a straight upper body.

Action:
Stretch and hold the elastic band with one arm, adjust the position of feet and supporting arm appropriately, so that the body continues to maintain the push-up posture.Pull down the arm holding the elastic band.Switch sides and continue until recommended times.

Tip:
Exhale and pull down, keeping 1-2S steady at the end of the action.Keep your torso level like steel plates and don't collapse.

Practical Application:
The three-point support plate is already a difficult movement. Combined with the elastic band resistance, the recruitment of core muscle groups is again improved, and active muscle control + passive weight load enable us to experience a different dynamic plate.

name: Elastic Belt Swallow Balance
desc:
Starting Position:
The upper body should be tilted forward, parallel to the ground. The right arm should be stretched out in front to grasp the elastic band. The left arm should be extended to the back of the body.Bend at the waist, use your left leg as a support leg, bend your knee slightly, and reach your right leg back to balance.

Action:
Pull the elastic band to one side of the body while keeping the upper body straight and slightly tilted back;The arms swing back and forth naturally;At the same time lunge leg unbend, right leg lift knee, after a short stay to restore the original.Repeat to recommended times.

Tip:
Keep the core close slightly and move smoothly.Fall slowly, exhale, and swing your arms and knees quickly.Keep moving on one leg to improve the finishing quality.

Practical Application:
One-leg training has great benefits for hip stimulation and lower limb stability.Through the swivel balance of large movement stimulation, greatly improve the efficiency of single-leg training, but also improve the difficulty of the movement.Beginners suggest that the back foot, keep balance, gradually transition into the advanced.

name: Exercise Ball Bridges
desc:
Starting Position:
Lie on your back with your back resting on the Swiss ball and your hips hanging in the air.Keep your feet shoulder-width apart and firmly on the ground.This is the Starting Position of the action.

Action:
Use the power of your hips to lift your hips up, making your body look like an arch bridge. Exhale.After a brief pause, return slowly to the Starting Position, inhaling.

Tips:
Keep your balance.

name: Exercise Ball Buzzsaw Plank
desc:
-Starting Position:
Place the Swiss ball in front of your body with both elbows resting on the Swiss ball and elbows directly under your shoulders. With your body in a plank position, tighten your core and make sure your body is in a straight line from head to toe.

-Action:
Keeping your core tight, drive the Swiss ball forward with your elbows in a slow, controlled motion. Then return to the starting position.

-Tip:
Exhale as you push forward and inhale as you pull back.
This movement is used to improve core stability, so it's important to coordinate your power through your lower back and hips to prevent your body from twisting or wobbling as you train.

name: Exercise Ball Circles
desc:
-Starting Position:
Place the Swiss ball in front of your body with both elbows resting on the Swiss ball and elbows directly under your shoulders. With your body in a plank position, tighten your core and make sure your body is in a straight line from head to toe.

-Action:
Keeping your core tight, draw your elbows in a slow, controlled circle clockwise or counterclockwise to turn the Swiss ball.

-Tip:
This action is used to improve core stability, so it's important to coordinate your power through your lower back and hips to prevent your body from twisting or wobbling as you train.

name: Exercise Ball Crunches
desc:
Starting Position:
Lie on your back with your back close to the Swiss ball and your back and waist straight.Keep your feet on the ground and your hands crossed in front of your chest.

Action:
Keep your lower back close to the ball at all times, contract your abs, lift your shoulders up with your belly volume, and exhale.Until the abdominal muscles contract to the limit.Pause briefly, then slowly return to the Starting Position while inhaling.

Tips:
Move slowly and make sure your body is balanced.If necessary, ask your partner for help.When carrying a heavy load, pay attention to the proper weight.

name: Exercise Ball Hyperextensions
desc:
Starting Position:
Lie prone on the Swiss ball with your upper body close to the ball and parallel to the ground.Keep your feet shoulder-width apart and firmly on the ground for balance.Hold a moderately heavy barbell piece with both hands under your chin.

Action:
Bend your back with your lower back, lift your upper body up, and exhale.After a brief pause, return slowly to the Starting Position, inhaling.

Tips:
The negative weight depends on the situation, pay attention to maintain their own balance.

name: Exercise Ball Plank
desc:
-Starting Position:
Place the Swiss ball in front of your body with both elbows resting on the Swiss ball and elbows directly under your shoulders. With your body in a plank position, tighten your core and make sure your body is in a straight line from head to toe.

-Action:
Control your body and the Swiss ball to remain stable for a certain amount of time.

-Tip:
Keep your breathing even and steady, don't hold your breath.
This movement is used to improve core stability, so it's important to coordinate your power through your lower back and hips to prevent your body from twisting or wobbling during the workout.

name: Exercise Ball Pull-In
desc:
Starting Position:
Place your calves on a Swiss ball and hold your hands in a push-up Position with your waist and back straight, hands shoulder-width apart, feet together.

Action:
Using the strength of your lower back, bend your legs forward and roll the rishi ball forward under your ankles while exhaling until your abs contract to their limit.Slowly return to Starting Position after a short stay.

Tips:
The movement should be slow and effective. Pay attention to the strength of the Swiss ball.

name: EZ Bar Curl
desc:
-Starting Position:
Feet apart, shoulder-width apart, lean forward slightly, knees slightly bent, keep body stable.
Arms hang naturally and hold the EZ bar in both hands with a slightly wider-than-shoulder-width grip.

-Action:
Keeping your upper arms stationary, use your elbows as a fulcrum to bend the EZ bar upward. Pause briefly after reaching maximum amplitude and slowly return to the starting position.

-Tip:
Exhale on the way up and inhale on the way down.
Stop training if you experience discomfort.
Stabilize the body without swaying and avoid borrowing from the lower extremities.
You can perform this movement in a seated position or in a pastor's chair.

name: Face Pull
desc:
-Starting Position:
With the rope pulley at shoulder height, hold the rope in both hands, palms facing each other, with the tigers' mouths facing the body. Arms straight, hands slightly above shoulder height.
Keep your feet open, shoulder width apart, and tilt your body slightly back. Keep a distance from the apparatus and make sure there is tension on the rope at all times.

-Action:
Bunch your shoulders back, pull your arms back, open your elbow joints outward, and lift your arms away from each other while lifting your arms, pulling the rope away from you to the sides, until the end of the rope is close to touching your head.

-Tips:
Keep your head and neck in a natural position, don't shrug your shoulders, and keep your core tight to keep your body stable.
Exhale as you pull and inhale as you return.

name: Farmer's Walk
desc:
-Starting Position:
Feet apart, shoulder-width apart or slightly narrower, back straight, core tight. Grasp weights firmly with both hands so that they are at your sides and your arms hang naturally.

-Action:
Slowly march forward in small steps.
Keep your back straight, shoulders open, shoulder blades down, head up, and spine in a neutral position as you travel.

-Tips:
Stop the workout when you experience discomfort.
Tighten your core throughout to avoid swaying your body.
You can opt for one-handed weights that can better improve core stability.

name: Fast Arm Swing
desc:
Starting Position:
Maintain a standing posture and prepare yourself to run.

Action:
Swing arms as if you are running and gradually accelerate. Legs should remain motionless.

Tip:
Maintain your balance during workout.

name: Fingertip Push-Up
desc:
-Starting Position:
Use your fingertips to brace yourself on the ground with your hands shoulder-width apart or slightly wider than shoulder-width apart. Head, torso and legs in a straight line.

-Action:
Keeping your body stable, slowly bend your elbows to lower your body, keeping your elbows close to your body. Pause briefly when the upper arm is nearly parallel to the ground. Push your body upward to return to the starting position.
When performing the movement, always keep your core muscles tight and your back straight, do not collapse or pucker your hips. Keep your neck naturally extended and don't tilt your head up or down excessively.

-Tip:
Inhale as you descend and exhale as you push up.
Stop training when experiencing discomfort.
Adjust the range of descent according to flexibility and personal ability.

name: Floor Press
desc:
-Starting Position:
Lie on your back on the ground with your knees bent, maintaining a stable position through your hips, feet, back, and head.
Keep your upper arms at an angle to your torso, in contact with the ground, forearms perpendicular to the ground, and weights in your hands.

-Action:
Chest power to push the weight upward until the arm is straight. Slowly return to the starting position.

-Tip:
Exhale as you push up and inhale as you return.
Stop training if you experience discomfort.
The type of weights can be changed according to the specific scenario of use.

name: Foam Rolling - Adductors
desc:
-Starting Position:
Lie prone with the supporting leg straight, the relaxing leg bent at the knee and hip, the thigh perpendicular to the torso, and the foam shaft perpendicular to the thigh. Place the foam shaft on the inner thigh of the relaxed side near the knee. Support your body with the other thigh and elbows, and use your body weight to press the inner thigh against the foam shaft.

-Action:
With a concerted effort from the support areas, roll the foam shaft toward a position near the hip and then back near the knee.
After completing the roll on one side, follow the same method for the front of the other thigh.

-Tip:
Take care to control the speed of the roll.
Small rolls or squeezes can be performed by stopping and adding pressure to areas of muscle tension or sore spots.

name: Foam Rolling - Calves
desc:
-Starting Position:
In a seated position, place the foam shaft under the calf of the relaxed leg, in contact with the back of the calf, near the knee. With your hands on the floor and your support leg bent at the knee, power up your hips and press the back of your calf against the foam shaft.

-Action:
With a concerted force from the support areas, roll the foam shaft toward a position near the ankle and then back near the knee.
After completing the roll on one side, follow the same method for the front of the other thigh.

-Tip:
Take care to control the speed of the roll.
You can increase the relaxation by resting the supporting leg on the back of the relaxing leg.
Small rolls or squeezes can be performed by stopping and adding pressure to areas of muscle tension or sore spots.

name: Foam Rolling - Chest
desc:
-Starting Position:
Prone. Place the foam shaft diagonally under the chest with the hand on the relaxed side naturally open outward and the other side hand supporting the floor.

-Action:
Push your body with force from the support area so that the foam shaft rolls in a small circle from the chest towards the armpits, focusing on relaxing the pectoralis major and pectoralis minor muscles.

-Tip:
Take care to control the speed of the roll.
Small rolls or squeezes can be performed by stopping and adding pressure to areas of muscle tension or sore spots.

name: Foam Rolling - Hamstrings
desc:
-Starting Position:
In a seated position, place the foam shaft underneath the relaxed leg, in contact with the back of the thigh, near the knee. With your hands on the ground and your support leg bent at the knee, power up your hips and press the back of your thighs against the foam shaft.

-Action:
With a concerted force from the support areas, roll the foam shaft toward a position near the hip and then back near the knee.
After completing the roll on one side, follow the same method for the front side of the other thigh.

-Tip:
Take care to control the speed of the roll.
You can increase the relaxation by resting the supporting leg in front of the relaxing leg.
Small rolls or squeezes can be performed by stopping and adding pressure to areas of muscle tension or sore spots.

name: Foam Rolling - Hips
desc:
-Starting Position:
In a seated position, place the foam shaft underneath the hip on the relaxed side. Brace one hand on the floor with the supporting leg bent at the knee and the foot of the relaxed side resting on the knee of the supporting leg. Press the back of the buttocks onto the foam shaft.

-Action:
With synergistic force from the support area, roll the foam shaft back and forth across the hips.
After completing the roll on one side, follow the same method for the front of the other thigh.

-Tip:
Take care to control the speed of the roll.
Small rolls or squeezes can be performed by stopping and adding pressure to areas of muscle tension or sore spots.

name: Foam Rolling - IT Bands
desc:
-Starting Position:
With the body supported sideways, place the foam shaft under the body in contact with the outer thigh of the relaxed leg, near the knee joint. The supporting leg is bent at the knee on the front side of the relaxed leg, supporting the body along with the hands. Press the outer thigh against the foam shaft with your body weight.

-Action:
With a synergistic force from the support areas, roll the foam shaft toward a position near the hip joint and then back near the knee.
After completing the roll on one side, follow the same method for the front of the other thigh.

-Tip:
Take care to control the speed of the roll.
Small rolls or squeezes can be performed by stopping and adding pressure to areas of muscle tension or sore spots.

name: Foam Rolling - Quads
desc:
-Starting Position:
Lying on your back with your legs straight, place the foam shaft on the front of one thigh near the knee. Support your body with the other thigh and elbows, and use your body weight to press the front of your thigh against the foam shaft.

-Action:
With a concerted effort from the support areas, roll the foam shaft toward a position near the hip and then back near the knee.
After completing the roll on one side, follow the same method for the other front thigh.

-Tip:
Take care to control the speed of the roll.
Small rolls or squeezes can be performed by stopping and adding pressure to areas of muscle tension or sore spots.
You can add to the relaxation by resting the supporting leg on the back of the relaxing leg.

name: Foam Rolling - Tibialis Anteriors
desc:
-Starting Position:
Lying prone, place the foam shaft under the calf of the relaxed leg, in contact with the front of the calf, near the knee. With the supporting leg in a kneeling position and arms supporting the body, use your body weight to press the front of the calf against the foam shaft.

-Action:
Drive the foam roller toward the ankle joint using coordinated force from support points, then return toward the knee area.
