After completing one side, repeat identical procedure on the contralateral anterior tibialis region.

-Tip:
Take care to control the speed of the roll.
Small rolls or squeezes can be performed by stopping and adding pressure to areas of muscle tension or sore spots.

name: Foam Rolling - Upper Back
desc:
-Starting Position:
Lie on your back with your knees bent and your feet firmly planted on the floor.
Place the foam shaft under the shoulder blades, avoiding direct contact with the lumbar or cervical spine.
Cross your arms over your head or rest them on your chest.

-Action:
With your core tight and hips slightly raised, drive your body back and forth through the power of your feet to slowly roll the foam shaft in the upper back to shoulder blade range.

-Tip:
Be careful to control the speed of rolling.
Small rolls or squeezes can be performed by stopping and adding pressure to areas of muscle tension or sore spots.

name: Foot Rolling
desc:
-Starting Position:
Sitting in a chair or standing position, place a fascia ball or tennis ball on the sole of one foot while balancing on the other.

-Action:
Slowly roll from heel to forefoot and back to heel, repeating the movement. Be careful to control the force to a mildly painful but tolerable level.
Roll laterally from side to side in the arch area to further relax the fascia.

-Tip:
Control plantar pressure to avoid injury and stop training if you experience discomfort.

name: Forward Jumping Lunges
desc:
Starting Position:
Start in a lunge position. The lower knee should be slightly off the ground.

Action:
Jump forward and swing the arms. Land in the opposite lunge position. Repeat.

Tips:
Use the arms to help propel the body forward.

name: Frog Pose
desc:
-Starting Position:
With hands and knees braced on the ground, slowly slide your knees out to the sides, keeping your thighs at a 90-degree angle to your body and your calves to your thighs.
Hook your feet back or press them into the ground and orient your toes in the same direction as your knees, avoiding inward or outward turning.
Head up, eyes flat in front of you, elbows on the ground.

-Action:
Push your body backward and feel the stretch in your inner thigh muscles.

-Tips:
Control the amplitude and stop the exercise if there is any discomfort.

name: Front Arm Dumbbell Raise
desc:
Starting Position:
Keep standing and hold one dumbbell with each hand in front of your thighs, palms facing back.

Action:
Raise the dumbbells forward then up until your arms are parallel to the ground and lower them back down after a short pause.

Tips:
Keep your arms extended throughout.

name: Front Raises With Bands
desc:
Starting Position:
Keep your body in a standing Position with your feet shoulder-width apart and your arms hanging down.Step on the elastic belt and hold the handle in your hand.

Action:
Bend your elbows slightly and lift your arms above shoulder level with the strength of your shoulders.

Tips:
Keep your back and waist straight during the exercise. Keep your movements slow and effective.

name: Front Squat
desc:
-Starting Position:
Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart or slightly wider than shoulder-width apart and your toes facing slightly diagonally forward. Raise both arms and hold a barbell above the anterior deltoid fascia, crossing your arms and gripping the barbell.
Keep your back naturally straight and tuck your stomach and chest.

-Action:
Squat down, bending your knees and hips, with your knees oriented in line with your toes.
Squat down until thighs are nearly parallel to the floor, pausing briefly.
Stomp and extend the lower leg to return to the starting position.

-Cue:
Inhale as you squat and exhale as you rise.
Stop training when you experience discomfort.
Tighten your core throughout, keeping your back straight and maintaining body stability.

name: Glute Bridge Hold
desc:
-Starting Position:
Lie on your back with your legs bent, heels on the ground, and feet shoulder-width or slightly widerapart.

-Action:
Lift your hips slowly upward so that your body forms a straight line from your shoulders to your knees.
When the hips are lifted to the highest point, hold the position for some time.

-Tip:
Keep your feet steady on the ground to provide stable support for your body.
Focus your attention on glute power without active force from your hands and feet.
Tighten your core while keeping your breathing even and not holding your breath.

name: Glute Stretch
desc:
-Starting Position:
Kneeling on the mat, bend one leg forward at the knee and place the calf across the front of the mat, with the heel of the foot near the other side of the abdomen.
Straighten the other side leg back with the instep of the foot on the floor.

-Action:
Lean your body forward slowly, keeping your abdomen close to the thigh of your front leg and keeping your neck naturally extended. Feel the stretch in your back and hips.

-Tips:
Don't hold your breath, keep your breathing rhythm.
Stop training if you experience discomfort.

name: Goblet Squat
desc:
-Starting Position:
Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart or slightly wider than shoulder-width apart and your toes facing slightly diagonally forward.
Hold dumbbells or kettlebells in both hands and hug them to your chest, elbows close to your sides.
Keep your back naturally straight and tuck in your stomach and chest.

-Action:
Squat down, bending your knees and hips, with your knees oriented in the same direction as your toes.
Squat down until thighs are nearly parallel to the floor, pausing briefly.
Stomp and extend the lower leg to return to the starting position.

-Cue:
Inhale as you squat and exhale as you rise.
Stop training when you experience discomfort.
Tighten your core throughout, keeping your back straight and maintaining body stability.

name: Greatest Stretch
desc:
-Starting Position:
Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart, keeping your spine naturally straight and your core tight.

-Action:
Slowly bend at the hips, lean down, stretch the back of your gluteal leg, and touch your hands to the floor.
Crawl your hands forward until your torso and thighs are in a line.
Take a big step forward with one foot on one side and straighten the back leg to reach the outside of the same hand and use the same hand to push the knee outward, stretching the inner thigh.
Rotate the thoracic spine and bring the elbow close to the palm of the opposite hand to stretch the back.
Rotate your body in the opposite direction, arms straight, fingers to the sky, eyes following the palms.
Drop your hand to the outside of your front lateral foot, shift your body weight back, straighten your front leg and hook your toes, stretching the back of your thigh and calf.
Return to the original position, extending your arms upward and leaning your body slightly back to stretch your chest, then drop your hands and pull your front side leg back to return to the push-up position.
Push your hips up and backward to form an inverted v-shape, stretching your back and the backs of your buttocks and legs.
Return to the push-up position and climb back up on your hands to reach your maximum amplitude and rise up.

-Tip:
You can pause briefly at each stretch to take a deep breath and feel the stretch.
Stop the workout if you experience discomfort.

name: Hack Squat Good Morning
desc:
-Starting Position:
Facing the Hacker, stand on the pedals with your feet shoulder-width apart or slightly wider and your toes facing slightly outward, about 15 degrees or so. Keep your body straight and shoulder carry the side cushions. Hold the handles with both hands to keep your body stable.

-Action:
Using the hips as an axis, slowly bend the hips forward while moving the hips backward and leaning the upper body forward.
Continue to lean your upper body forward until your body is roughly parallel to the floor, feeling the stretch in your hips and the back of your thighs. Push your hips forward to return to the starting position.

-Tip:
Inhale as you lean forward and exhale as you rise.
Tighten your core to prevent spinal injuries.
Stop training if you feel discomfort during the movement.

name: Half Crimp
desc: Please follow your training program for 4-finger hang or 3-finger hang. We generally dont recommend 2-finger hang unless you have specific training goals, to prevent injury. The same rule applies to the depth of the hold as well.

name: Hammer Curl
desc:
-Starting Position:
Feet apart, shoulder-width apart, body slightly leaning forward, knees slightly bent, keep the body stable.
Hold a dumbbell in each hand, arms hanging down naturally, dumbbells located on both sides of the body, palms facing each other.

-Action:
Keeping your upper arms stationary and using your elbows as a fulcrum, bend the dumbbells upward along the sides of your body. Keep your palms facing each other at all times, and track the dumbbells as close to your body as possible. Pause briefly when you reach your maximum lift and slowly return to the starting position.

-Tip:
Exhale on the way up and inhale on the way down.
Stop training if you experience discomfort.
Stabilize your body and don't sway, avoid borrowing force from your lower extremities.

name: Hamstring Stretch
desc:
-Starting Position:
Stand facing a support with one leg raised, heel on support, toes hooked and legs straight.
Keep your hips stable, spine extended, and hands can be on your knees or raised above your head.

-Actions:
Lean forward on your hip axis, keeping your chest as close to your thighs as possible and avoiding arching your back or shrugging your shoulders.

-Tips:
Keep breathing normally.
Keep the toes of the leg being pressed in the same direction as the knee.
Adjust range according to flexibility to avoid overstretching.

name: Handstand Push-Up
desc:
-Starting Position:
Start upside down, facing the wall, with your hands on the floor and arms straight. Keep your legs together and rest your feet on the wall. Core tight, torso and legs in a straight line.

-Action:
Flexing your elbows, slowly lower your body until your upper arms are nearly parallel to the floor. With your shoulders firing, extend your elbows to drive your body back to the starting position.

-Tip:
Exhale as you push up and inhale as you descend.
Do not over lock the elbow joint when extending the elbow. Stop training when experiencing discomfort.

name: Handstands
desc:
Starting Position:
Stand facing the wall with your arms down and your upper body straight.

Action:
Keep your arms on the ground and your elbows from bending. Immediately lift your legs up and press your legs against the wall. Keep your arms in a handstand position until the recommended time.Or gradually bend your elbows so that your body sinks until your head is about to touch the ground. Lift your arms up and return to the handstand position. Repeat until the recommended number of times.

Tip:
Keep your balance. For safety reasons, beginners should avoid doing this or exercise with a companion to avoid injury.

name: Hang with 135 Degree Elbow
desc: Please follow your training program for 4-finger hang or 3-finger hang. We generally dont recommend 2-finger hang unless you have specific training goals, to prevent injury. The same rule applies to the depth of the hold as well.

name: Hang with 90 Degree Elbow
desc: Please follow your training program for 4-finger hang or 3-finger hang. We generally dont recommend 2-finger hang unless you have specific training goals, to prevent injury. The same rule applies to the depth of the hold as well.

name: Hangboard Pull-ups
desc:
-Starting Position:
Hang from the hang point with your hands, palms facing forward.

-Action:
Pull yourself upward with both hands until the height of your chin reaches the height of your palms and lower yourself after a brief pause.

-Tip:
You can adjust the difficulty of the exercise by adjusting the spacing of the hanging points and the number of hanging fingers.
Inhale as you raise yourself and exhale as you lower yourself.

name: Hanging Leg Raise
desc:
Starting Position:
Hang from the horizontal bar with your arms straight, using a wide or middle grip on the bar, legs straight down, pelvis slightly backward.

Action:
Use the strength of your lower torso to lift your legs until they are at a 90-degree angle, holding the position and slowly returning to normal.
Note:
Weight increase should be appropriate, as much as possible to maintain the balance and stability of the body in order to prevent sports injury.

name: Hanging Windshield Wiper
desc:
Starting Position:
Stand in front of the parallel bars with your arms hanging down and your upper body straight.

Action:
Grasp the upper horizontal bar with both hands, use the strength of the waist and abdomen to lift the legs, until the feet and head parallel;Use the waist and abdomen force to twist the lower limbs to the left, until unable to twist, after a short stay to twist to the other side, repeat this movement until the recommended times.

Tip:
Pay attention to the control of the body movement rhythm, the exercise intensity is large, before the exercise should be fully warmed up.

name: Hex Bar Deadlift
desc:
-Starting Position:
Feet are shoulder-width apart or slightly wider, toes naturally abducted by 10-15, knees oriented in line with toes.
The body is centered on the hexagonal bar and the hands are palms facing each other, holding the handles of the hexagonal barbell.
Keep your spine in a neutral position, avoid arching your back or recoiling, and keep your core tight.
Flex the hips (sit back at the hips) while bending the knees and bringing the thighs close to horizontal.

-Action:
Inhale to prepare, and exhale as your glutes and legs fire, pulling the barbell vertically upward, keeping the barbell close to the midline of your body.
Hip extension (hip thrust forward) is synchronized with knee extension, standing completely straight at the top of the movement.
Lower slowly at a controlled rate, prioritizing hip flexion to guide the barbell down, keeping the spine neutral.

-Tip:
Exhale on the pull-up and inhale on the lowering.
For beginners, less stress on the spine and more controlled movement.

name: HighKnees
desc:
Starting Position:
Keep your chest out and stomach in

Action:
Keep your knees and toes forward and lift your legs slightly above your hips


Tips:
Strike the ground on the ball of your foot

name: High Knees Against Wall
desc:
Starting Position:
Lean forward with your hands against a wall, keeping your arms straight.

Action:
Alternately bring each of your knees up until it's in line with your belly and repeat at a steady pace.

Tip:
Keep pushing against the wall with your arms to balance your upper body.

name: High Pulley Crunches
desc:
Starting Position:
Kneel in front of a high pulley with ropes.Grab the rope with both hands and pull down until your hands are on either side of your cheek.

Action:
Use the strength of your lower back to slowly pull the rope down until your elbow moves to the middle of your thigh, pause briefly, and slowly return to the Starting Position.

Tips:
Weight is added according to the actual situation, waist and abdomen hair force to improve the training effect.

name: Hip Adductions With Bands
desc:
Starting Position:
Wrap elastic tape around a post or other solid object.In a standing Position, the left side of your body is facing the column and the elastic band is wrapped around your right ankle.

Action:
Keeping the upper body straight, lift your right leg and knee straight and try to lift it as far away as possible.Then pause briefly and return to the Starting Position.

Tips:
It requires a certain rhythm and balance.

name: Hip Thrust
desc:
-Starting Position:
Place a barbell in the lower abdominal area above the pubic bone, cushioning the pressure with a towel or mat.
Rest your upper back against the bench with the lower edge of your shoulder blades aligned with the edge of the bench.
Feet are shoulder-width apart or slightly wider, toes abducted 15, calves perpendicular to the floor.
Core tightens and spine remains neutral to avoid collapsing the back.

-Action:
Glute contraction pushes the hips upward so that the shoulders-hips-knee are in a straight line. Strong gluteus maximus contraction and pause for 1-2 seconds.
Control the centrifugal phase by slowly lowering the hips to the starting position, maintaining gluteal muscle tone.

-Tip:
Exhale on the upward push and inhale on the lowering.
Core tightens to avoid lumbar pronation and injury.

name: Incline Bench Press
desc:
Starting Position:
Lie down on your back on the incline bench and grasp the barbell with both hands in a medium-grip Position.

Action:
Push the barbell straight up until your elbows are close to being locked and lower it back slowly after a short pause.

Tips:
Breathe out while pushing the bar and breathe in while lowering it back.

name: Incline Dumbbell Bench Press
desc:
-Starting Position:
The bench press bench is at an angle to the floor. Lie on your back on the bench press bench, maintaining a stable position through your feet, hips, back, and head.
The upper arms are at an angle to the torso, in contact with the floor, the forearms are perpendicular to the floor, and the dumbbells are held in the hands.

-Action:
Chest power push the dumbbells upward until your arms are straight. Slowly return to the starting position.

-Tip:
Exhale as you push up and inhale as you return.
Stop the workout if you experience discomfort.

name: Incline Dumbbell Flys
desc:
Starting Position:
Lie down on your back on an incline bench and grab one dumbbell with each hand at shoulder height, elbows at 90 degree angles.

Action:
Raise the dumbbells until they are side by side on top of you and slowly lower them back after a short pause.

Tips:
Try to maintain the same angle in your elbows throughout.

name: Incline Leg Press
desc:
Starting Position:
Lie down on the bench, hold the weight with your knees close to 90 degree angles and grab the provided handles with both hands.

Action:
Push the weight stack by extending your legs and let it slowly swing back after a short pause.

Tips:
Breathe out when pushing out and breathe in when letting the weight stack swing back.

name: Incline Leg Raise
desc:
Starting Position:
Sitting on a leg lift, place your hips against the seat cushion and place your feet shoulder-width apart on the platform.Grab the handle and apply force from the heel to release the safety latch.

Action:
Inhale and slowly lower the load until the knees are 90 degrees.Pause for a moment, then push the weight strongly up through your heel to return to the Starting Position, then exhale as you push up through the midpoint of the action.

Tips:
Your knees should be slightly bent at the beginning of the movement and not fully extended during the lift.

name: Incline Push-Up
desc:
-Starting Position:
Brace your hands on a higher platform, such as a stool or box. Hands are spaced shoulder-width apart or slightly wider than shoulder-width apart. Head, torso and legs are in a straight line.

-Action:
Keeping your body stable, slowly bend your elbows to lower your body, keeping your elbows close to your body. Pause briefly when the upper arm is nearly parallel to the ground. Push your body upward to return to the starting position.
When performing the movement, always keep your core muscles tight and your back straight, do not collapse or pucker your hips. Keep your neck naturally extended and don't tilt your head up or down excessively.

-Tip:
Inhale as you descend and exhale as you push up.
Stop training when experiencing discomfort.
Adjust the range of descent based on flexibility and individual ability.
Decrease the difficulty of the movement by increasing the height of the hands and decrease the height to increase the difficulty.

name: Incline Walking
desc:
Starting Position:
Keep your stance on the treadmill.

Action:
Turn on the treadmill, adjust your running speed and slope to suit you, and walk at a set pace until the recommended time.

Tip:
Pay attention to adjust the speed and slope of the treadmill.

name: Indoor Rower
desc:
Starting point:
In a sitting position with your feet on the pedals, grasp the handles on the pullies of the rowing machine and slightly arch your back until you feel a small tension or clear stretch in the back muscles. Keep your knees slightly bent while avoiding locking your back out.
 
Action:
Straighten your arms and keep your body fixed. Hold the handle and pull back until the handle is close to the abdomen. You should feel the tightening of the back muscles, pause for 1 second, and then slowly resume the movement.
 
Tip:
Exhale during your pull and inhale when returning the handles.

name: Inner Thigh Stretch
desc:
-Starting Position:
Sit on the floor with your spine straight and legs straight ahead.

-Action:
Bend your knees with the soles of your feet facing each other and close to the perineum, holding your feet or ankles with both hands.
Open your knees to the sides and try to keep your outer thighs as close to the floor as possible.
Breathe deeply. Hold for 30 seconds to 5 minutes, adjusting to individual ability.

-Tip:
You can press your hands on your inner thighs to help bring your knees down, or bend forward to deepen the stretch.

name: Inverse Nordic Curl
desc:
-Starting Position:
Kneel with your torso in a straight line with your thighs and your knees open to shoulder width. Hands are clasped to the chest or hang naturally.

-Action:
Using the knee as an axis, tilt the thighs and torso back, tightening the core to ensure that the area above the knee is in a straight line. The front of the thigh generates force to control the speed of the backward tilt until it is at its maximum amplitude. Active force from the front thighs pulls the body slowly back to the starting position.

Tips:
The amplitude of the movement depends on the flexibility of the individual, control the amplitude to avoid strains.
Inhale when you lean back and exhale when you return.

name: J Lo S
desc:
Starting Position:
Lie on your side with your legs bent at perigee.

Action;
Lift the apogee leg up 45 and slowly lower it after a short stay. Repeat the action to the recommended number of times, then switch sides.

Tip:
When the distal leg is raised to 45, the leg can be stopped appropriately to improve the exercise effect.

name: Jogging
desc:
Starting Position:
Maintain a standing posture, arms naturally hang, upper body straight.

Action:
Run at a slow pace according to your situation.

Tip:
Adjust your breathing and rhythm and keep your body relaxed.

name: Jumping Jacks
desc:
Starting Position:
Stand with your feet together, arms bent, hands touching in front of your chest, elbows at your sides.

Action:
Jump out at your sides with your feet, elbows up, hands apart.Then immediately jump back to the Starting Position, followed by the arms.Repeat until recommended number of times.

Tips:
Keep your body straight.

name: Jumping Lunges
desc:
Starting Position:
Start in the lunge position.Lower knee should be slightly off the ground.

Action:
Jump vertically up, with your arms swinging to keep your balance as you lunge, opposite the lunge position.

Tips:
Use your arms to help your body bounce up and balance.

name: Kettlebell Windmill
desc:
Starting Position:
Holding a kettlebell while standing, hold it over your right shoulder while pushing it over the same shoulder.Feet shoulder-width apart.

Action;
The arms holding kettlebell remain still, and the body begins to lean to the other side until the waist is bent beyond bending, return to original shape after a short stay, repeat the action to the recommended number of times before changing sides.

Tip:
Pay attention to maintain the rhythm of this movement, to avoid lumbar movement injury.

name: Knee Hug
desc:
-Starting Position:
Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart, keeping your spine naturally straight and your core tight.

-Action:
Bend one leg at the knee and lift up to the chest.
Wrap your hands around the underside of the knee and lift up to chest position, keeping the supporting leg upright.
Hold for 1-2 seconds then switch legs and alternate.

-Tip:
You can practice this in place or alternate while traveling.
You can also tiptoe on the toes of the standing leg while stretching to stretch further.

name: Knee-Up Lunges
desc:
Starting Position:
Start in a lunge position with a big step back. The lower knee should be slightly off the ground.

Action:
Raise the back knee up to 90-degree angles and slowly step back after a short pause. Repeat the exercise on one side before switching to the side.

Tips:
Maintain good balance and keep your back straight throughout.

name: Knee-Up Walking Lunges
desc:
Starting Position:
Start in a lunge position. The lower knee should be slightly off the ground.

Action:
Take a controlled step forward and bend your knee to 90-degree angles and slowly bring yourself back up after a short pause. Alternate feet between repetitions.

Tips:
Keep your back straight throughout.

name: Kneeling Ab Wheel Rollout
desc:
-Starting Position:
Kneel on the floor with your knees, hands on the handles of the ab wheel, arms straight, and the ab wheel directly in front of your body. Keep your back straight and core muscles tight.

-Action:
Slowly and steadily roll the ab wheel forward while moving your body weight forward. Keep your arms straight and core tight during the roll.
Depending on your ability and the tolerance level of your abdominal muscles, control how far the wheel rolls forward.
After reaching the maximum rolling distance, slowly pull the wheel back to the starting position.

Tips:
Inhale as you roll forward and exhale as you pull back.

name: Kneeling Anti-Rotational Press
desc:
-Starting Position:
The pulley of the rope is at chest height. Kneel with your body side to the apparatus, keeping a distance to keep some tension on the rope. Clasp the handles to your chest with both hands, tightening your core to ensure your upper body is straight and not swaying.

-Action:
Push the handles forward until your arms are straight, then return to the starting position. During the push and pull, you need to use your core to resist the lateral pull and prevent your torso from rotating.

-Tip:
Exhale as you push forward and inhale as you recover.
The movement can be performed on one knee or standing, and all parts of the body except the arms need to be stabilized during the exercise.

name: Kneeling Cable Woodchop
desc:
-Starting Position:
Kneeling position with the pulley of the rope above the head, on the side of the body. The front side leg is close to the direction of the apparatus.
Hold the ends of the handles with both hands, arms straight, handles tilted, lower ends at shoulder height, palms angled down.

-Action:
With the core firing, the upper body rotates to the opposite side while the arms stroke in a diagonal direction along the body in an angled downward chopping motion.
After reaching maximum amplitude, the body and arms slowly return to the starting position on the original trajectory.

-Tip:
Exhale on the downward chop and inhale on the return.
Handles can be made of straightened soft rope or long poles.

name: Kneeling Position And Do The Top Hip
desc:
Starting Position:
Keep your knees together on the mat, knees bent, upper body straight, hands holding the barbell on your chest.

Action:
Lunge forward with one foot and lift the bar with both hands. Hold the bar briefly and slowly return to normal.

Tip:
Pay attention to the stretching of your body during the exercise. Stretch your groin thoroughly to avoid injury.

name: Kneeling Push-Ups
desc:
Starting Position:
Keep your upper body in the push-up position. Bend your lower knees and hold the floor. Place your lower legs behind your hips without touching the ground.

Action;
Using chest and arm strength, the body slowly sinks until the tip of the nose is about to touch the ground. After a short stay, the body slowly recovers.Repeat to recommended times.

Tip:
Improve the quality of your movements. Keep your upper body straight as you rise and fall, keeping your elbows at your sides.

name: Lat Pulldowns
desc:
-Starting Position:
Sit in a seated position, keeping your lower extremities stabilized, your back straight and slightly tilted back. Palms forward, arms extended to just above head, hold handles of apparatus.

-Action:
Power up at the back and drive the elbows downward. Pause briefly after reaching maximum range of motion.
Use your back to control the speed and slowly return to the starting position.

-Tips:
Exhale on the pull down and inhale on the release.
Keep your shoulders relaxed and your body stable.

name: Lateral Band Walks
desc:
Starting Position:
Secure the elastic band around the lower leg.Its Position as close as possible to the knee Position is relatively easy, the more down is more difficult, maintain the elastic belt Position is fixed, the body is in a standing posture, knees and buttocks slightly bent, two feet open and shoulder width, head and chest, keep the back and waist straight.

Action:
Lower your weight and take a slow step sideways.Tip your toes forward and keep your weight low.Once you've done this, do the same with the other leg.Slowly step out of the side and tighten the elastic band.Keep your feet shoulder-width apart and maintain tension.

Tips:
Move slowly and rhythmically, keeping upper body straight.

name: Lateral Dumbbell Raise
desc:
Starting Position:
Stand with your feet apart, your back straight, your arms hanging at your sides, and your hands holding the dumbbells.

Action:
Lift the dumbbell to shoulder level, elbows slightly bent, and rest for 3-6 seconds to return to Starting Position.

Tips:
Keep your body still, with only the driving muscles in motion.

name: Lateral Leg Swings
desc:
-Starting Position:
Standing position, body straight, arms crossed for balance or holding on to a support point.

-Action:
Support the ground with one leg, keep the torso stable, straighten the other leg and swing from one side of the body to the other, try to keep the leg straight and swing evenly.

Tips:
Keep breathing during the swing.
Increase the amplitude of the swing as much as possible based on flexibility.
Keep your core tight and your torso stable to avoid swaying during the swing.

name: Lateral Raise-Machine
desc:
-Starting Position:
Sit in a seated position, maintaining postural stability through foot, hip, and back contact with the apparatus. Hold the handles of the apparatus with both hands, forearms in contact with the cushions.

-Action:
With a shoulder strike, lift the elbows to raise the handles to the sides. Pause briefly after the upper arms and the floor are nearly parallel. Power up to control speed and slowly return to the starting position.

-Cue:
Exhale as you lift the elbow and exhale as you return.
Stop training if you feel discomfort during the movement.

name: Lateral Raises With Bands
desc:
Starting Position:
Maintain a standing posture with your back straight, feet shoulder-width apart and tramping on elastic rope, hands hanging naturally at your sides and gripping the elastic rope.

Action:
Keeping the elbow slightly bent, contract the deltoid and lift the arm to a horizontal Position. At the highest point, the shoulder is slightly higher than the elbow and the elbow is slightly higher than the wrist.

Tips:
Pay attention to the slow motion range, keep the waist and back straight at all times.

name: Lateral Squats or Side Squats
desc:
-Starting Position:
Stand with your feet open and wide, toes pointed outward. Hands clasped in front of chest.

-Action:
Squat to one side, noting that the squatting leg is oriented in the same direction as the toes. Once the thigh is nearly parallel to the floor, pause briefly and return to the starting position. Alternate between right and left legs or complete one set with each leg on one side.

-Tip:
Stop the movement if you experience discomfort.
Weights can be used to make the movement more difficult.

name: Lateral step ups
overview: Lateral step-ups involve stepping one foot sideways onto a step and balancing on that leg as you hover the other foot off the floor.

name: Lean Over And Touch Your Shoulders Alte
desc:
Starting Position:
Keep the push-ups ready position, and the distance between your feet can be opened according to your own situation.

Action
Hold with one hand on your feet, and touch your shoulder with the other hand. Then pull your hand back and repeat with the other arm.Alternate arms for the recommended number of repetitions.

Tip
Improve movement quality, reduce body shaking, keep the body straight all the way.

name: Leg Extensions
desc:
Starting Position:
Sit down on the bench and Position your ankles against the foot pads.

Action:
Raise your feet by extending your legs and slowly lower them back down slowly after a pause.

Tips:
Keep your back straight throughout.

name: Leg Raise Toe to Bar
desc:
Starting Position:
Hang yourself on the horizontal bar with your arms straight out, using either a wide grip or a middle grip.Legs straight down, pelvis slightly back.

Action:
Lift your legs above your head using the strength of your lower back and abdomen, hold the position slightly and slowly return to your original position.

Tip:
Pay attention to the process of restoring the original should use abdominal strength to slow the body down.

name: Leg Swing Front and Back
desc:
-Starting Position:
Standing position, body straight, arms crossed for balance or holding on to a support point.

-Actions:
Support the ground with one leg, keeping the torso stable, straighten the other leg and swing the leg back and forth with the hip joint as the axis. Try to keep the leg straight and swing evenly.

Tip:
Keep breathing during the swing.
Increase the amplitude of the swing as much as possible based on flexibility.
Keep your core tight and your torso stable to avoid swaying during the swing.

name: Lie On And High Knees
desc:
Starting Position:
Lean on the ground, with your hands on the floor in a push-up position and your arms straight out.Then bend one leg forward, knees close to chest, and make a motion to prepare for the climb.

Action:
Keep your arms straight, rotate your legs quickly, and do the climbing.Repeat with alternate legs for 20-30 seconds.

Tips:
Maintain high standards, high quality and high speed during practice.

name: Lie On One Leg Supine Hip And Knee
desc:
Starting Position:
Lie flat on a yoga mat with your knees at a 90-degree Angle, both knees together and one knee not bent. Place your hands flat on the floor and your arms at your sides.

Action:
Raise your hips and hips as high as you can, while bending your straight knees as high as you can and lowering them slowly after a brief pause.Continue until recommended number of times.

Tips:
Pay attention to the power source and keep your balance.

name: Lie on Your Back Glute Bridge
desc:
Starting Position:
Lie flat on a yoga mat with your knees at a 90-degree Angle and place your hands flat on the floor with your arms at your sides.

Action:
Raise the hips and hips as high as possible, leaving the rest of the body as it is, and lowering them slowly after a brief pause.

Tips:
Pay attention to the power source, do not use your hands and feet for power.

name: Loaded carry
overview: Heavy weight in each hand. Axial loading for bones. Walk. Each step lift knee up for single leg exercise purpose. Do 20 steps.

name: Loaded creeper march
overview: Hold heavyweight in hands. Bend slightly at knees. Walk on tip toes. Exercises soleus muscle.

name: Low Cable Flys
desc:
Starting Position:
Keep your stance under the gantry, and adjust your two griphors to be on either side of the gantry and pull one with each hand.

Action:
Use the strength of the shoulder and the big arm to pull the ring up slowly until the arm is straight.

Tips:
Both arms require simultaneous power, the footwall stable good center of gravity.

name: Low Pulley Biceps Curls
desc:
Starting Position:
In a standing Position, hold the rope handle shoulder-width apart with both hands.Always keep your elbows close to your torso and your upper arms in place.

Action:
The forearm pulls hard on the rope grip until the biceps fully contract and the bar reaches shoulder height.Pause for a moment and slowly bring the straight bar back to the Starting Position while inhaling.

Tips:
During movement, only the forearm is in motion, and the rest of the body remains stationary.

name: Lucky Cat
desc:
-Starting Position:
Standing position, feet shoulder-width apart, back straight, arms outstretched on both sides of the body, elbows bent 90 degrees, arms parallel to the ground.

-Action:
Using the upper arm as an axis, rotate the forearm upward until the forearm is perpendicular to the ground, pause briefly and then return to the starting position.

-Tip:
You can practice this with your bare hands or add weights such as dumbbells.

name: Lunge Down
desc:
Starting Position:
Keep standing and hold the bar with both hands.

Action:
Hold the lunge with your legs outstretched and place the barbell with your hands below your hip joint. Use your hip strength to push your body down and up, alternating your legs in the same rhythm.

Tip:
Pay attention to the stretching of your body during the exercise. Stretch your groin thoroughly to avoid injury.

name: Lunge Pulls
desc:
Starting Position:
Stand with your feet in a lunge position, bend your front leg at the knee about 90 degrees, straighten your back leg, keep your body upright, and tighten your core.

Action:
Lift the back leg up quickly, keeping the heel as close to the buttocks as possible, while keeping the supporting leg in an ""S"" position, and not over-extending the knee.
When landing on the ground, use the forefoot to land on the ground without the heel touching the ground, and try to land as close as possible to the lower part of the body.
Swing your arms naturally to maintain balance.

Tips:
If you are lunge pulling up while traveling, after the lifting leg lands, the supporting leg coordinates to follow and travel forward to keep the movement consistent.

name: Lunge Sideways From Hip To Hip
desc:
Starting Position:
Keep standing and hold the bar with both hands.

Action:
Hold the leg position on the side, place the barbell in the chest position with both hands, use the hip force to press the body down and up, keep the same rhythm on both sides alternately.

Tip:
Pay attention to the stretching of your body during the exercise. Stretch your groin thoroughly to avoid injury.

name: Lunge Stretch
desc:
-Starting Position:
Body upright, take a big step forward with one foot on one side. Bend the front side leg at the knee with the thigh parallel to the floor. Rear side leg extended. Maintain balance with both hands.

-Action:
Lower your hips to stretch your lower leg muscles.

-Tip:
Stop training if you experience discomfort.

name: Lunge Up With A Heavy Bow
desc:
Starting Position:
Keep standing and hold the bar with both hands.

Action:
Hold the leg position on the side, place the barbell in the chest position with both hands, use the hip force to press the body down and up, keep the same rhythm on both sides alternately.

Tip:
Pay attention to the stretching of your body during the exercise. Stretch your groin thoroughly to avoid injury.

name: Lunge With Elastic Band
desc:
Starting Position:
Stand with the elastic strap on the side of your body. Pull the elastic strap with your hands to the standing position and fix the elastic strap.

Action:
Keep the length of the elastic band constant and bend the knee to complete the lunge.Repeat lunges as many times as recommended.

Tip:
While maintaining a 90-degree Angle between the hips and knees, move the center of gravity up and down, complete the standard lunge, and other movements.

Practical Application:
As the most simple and practical functional training movement, lunge squats not only strengthen the core, but also train the strength and stability of lower limbs, which is actually the golden movement for runners' physical training.

name: Lying Face Down Plate Neck Resistance
desc:
Starting Position:
Lie prone on the bench (feet stabilized) and hold a dumbbell with both hands behind your neck.

Action:
Raise your upper body up until it is parallel to the floor and lower it back after a short pause.

Tips:
Breathe out while raising yourself and breathe in while lowering yourself back.

name: Lying Face Up Plate Neck Resistance
desc:
Starting Position:
Lie flat on your back in your gym chair and place the bell piece on your forehead.The shoulders should be slightly over the chair and the head should be completely over the chair.

Action:
Place the bell piece firmly on your forehead and slowly lean back in a semicircle while inhaling.Lift your head, return to the Starting Position by half circle, and exhale.Hold the contracting Position for a short time.

Tips:
Keep the rhythm step by step, do not force too hard, weight should not be too high.

name: Lying Leg Curls
desc:
Starting Position:
Lean over the mat and keep the thighs in contact with the floor.

Action:
Use lower limb strength to fold crus as far as possible, heel is close to hip as far as possible, return to start Position slowly after brief stay.

Tips:
The rest of the body should remain stationary except for the movement of the calf.

name: Lying Leg Curls with Resistance Band
desc:
-Starting Position:
Lie down on a bench or on the floor. One side of the elastic band is secured at the same height and the other side is hooked around the ankles of both legs.
Legs are opened shoulder-width apart, knees are slightly bent, and the elastic band is kept under some tension.

-Action:
Power up the back of your thighs and quickly bend your knees. Once you reach maximum amplitude, slowly return to the starting position.

-Tips:
Exhale as you bend the knee and inhale as you return.
Stop the exercise if you experience discomfort.
Adjust the resistance according to the elasticity of different elastic bands.
Exercises can be performed on one leg.

name: Machine Crunches
desc:
Starting Position:
Sitting on the apparatus, place your feet under the harness and hold the upper handle.Bend your arms at 90 degrees and rest your triceps on the harness.

Action:
Use your waist and abdomen to bend the upper part of your body while lifting your legs and exhaling.
Pause for a second, slowly return to the Starting Position, and inhale.

Tips:
When practicing, add weights according to their own conditions to avoid injury;Do it slowly and in control.Focus on the abdomen and relax the legs and feet.

name: Machine Hyperextention
desc:
Starting Position:
Sit on the machine and adjust the weight of the machine.

Action:
Press the instrument backward with the strength of the back of the waist until the instrument is extended to the limit.

Tips:
Pay attention to the rest of the body.

name: Machine Reverse Fly
desc:
-Starting Position:
Sit in a seated position, maintaining postural stability through foot, hip, and chest contact with the apparatus. Arms are raised in front of you and both hands grip the handles of the apparatus.

-Actions:
Power the back of the shoulders, driving the handles outward. Pause briefly after reaching maximum amplitude.
Control your speed and slowly return to the starting position.

-Cue:
Exhale as you expand outward and exhale as you return.
Slightly flex the elbow to reduce stress on the elbow and analyze presses for injuries.
Stop training if you feel discomfort during the movement.

name: Med Ball Push Press
desc:
-Starting Position:
Feet apart, shoulder-width apart, hold medicine ball in front of chest with both hands.

-Action:
Squat: Bend your hips and knees and squat at an even pace. Squat until thighs are parallel to the ground or slightly lower.
Upward Push:
Use the power of your legs and hips to quickly pedal up and push your body upward. As your body pushes upward, quickly straighten your arms and push the medicine ball upward. Transfer the power from your legs to your hips and then through your spine to your upper body to provide a strong push to launch the medicine ball.

-Tip:
Keep your body balanced and stable.
Inhale as you squat and exhale as you push up.
Evenly descend to build power and push up quickly to release it.
The leg stomps and arm push-ups should be coordinated to form a coherent whole, making full use of the explosive power of each joint.

name: Medicine Ball Push-Ups
desc:
Starting Position:
Lie face down on the floor, keeping your back and waist straight.Keep your hands shoulder-width apart, one on the ball and the other on the ground.Stand on your toes with your legs about hip width apart to support your balance.

Action:
Keeping your body straight, slowly bend your arms downward while inhaling.Until the chest is close to the ground.Then quickly unbend your arms, push your body back into the Starting Position, and exhale.After a short stay, move on to the next practice.

Tips:
During the practice, pay attention to the stability of the ball and keep the waist and back straight.Exercises are similar to push-ups.

name: Military Press
desc:
-Starting Position:
Standing Position. Keep your torso slightly back and core tight to keep your torso stable.
Hold a barbell in your hands with a slightly wider-than-shoulder-width grip and small arms perpendicular to the floor. Place the barbell in a clavicular or upper chest position with elbows slightly forward, tightening the shoulder blades and core.

-Action:
Push vertically upward, tilting your head back slightly to allow the barbell to track away from your chin (do not over-tilt your lumbar spine).
Reach the highest point with your arms straight, barbell directly above your head, and torso straight.
Lower the barbell back to its original position along the same trajectory.

-Tip:
Exhale on the upward push and inhale on the lowering.
Stop training if you experience discomfort.
Keep your body stable and do not sway.

name: Mountain Climbers
desc:
Starting Position:
Lean on the ground, with your hands on the floor in a push-up Position and your arms straight out.Then bend one leg forward, knees close to chest, and make a motion to prepare for the climb.

Action:
Keep your arms straight, rotate your legs quickly, and do the climbing.Repeat with alternate legs for 20-30 seconds.

Tips:
Maintain high standards, high quality and high speed during practice.

name: Neck Bridge Prone
desc:
Starting Position:
Keep all your weight on your stomach and your hands and knees on the floor.Place your head between your hands and touch the ground gradually, keeping your legs straight and hips up.

Action:
Lift your hands off the ground and transfer weight to your head.Hold the bridge Position for a while, carefully letting your hands and knees return to the ground.

Tips:
This movement should be done slowly, as long as there is serious discomfort or neck problems to stop the movement, and pay attention to the size of the motion.

name: Neck Flexion With Positive Pressure Of
desc:
Starting Position:
Put your fingers behind your head and keep your upper body straight.

Action:
With both hands behind the head pressing forward slowly resist using the neck muscles to bring your head back to the starting position. You should feel the muscles in theck being engaged

Tips:
When the head is flexed and stretched, the body should not lean forward and backward, be careful not to exert too much force, step by step, to avoid neck sprain. Do not allow any rotation of the neck, but only flexion and extension.

name: Nordic Hamstring Curl
desc:
-Starting Position:
Secure your ankles, either with a barbell, Nordic jerk device, or look for a helper.
Kneel on both knees, thighs perpendicular to torso and floor, arms crossed or clasped in front of chest, core tight.

-Action:
Lean your body forward, with the back of your thighs firing to control the speed of your body's movement. Slowly bring the chest closer to the floor. Ensure that your shoulders, hips, and knees are in a straight line during the movement and do not bend at the hips.
When the body reaches the bottom, you can power back up with the back of your thighs to return to the starting position, or you can use your hands to support yourself.

Tips:
Inhale as you lower your body and exhale as you return to the starting position.
Stop training when you experience discomfort.
You can use an elastic band to hang back to reduce the difficulty of the movement.

name: Oblique V-Ups
desc:
Starting Position:
Body side on the mat, legs bent, ham and crus Angle is about 60 degrees, knee vertical to the ground, one foot on the other foot feet, upper body tilt, stepping on the anchor of the ipsilateral shoulders off the ground, on the other side against the ground, the upper arm on the other side of the shoulder, under the arm unbend natural on the mat.

Action:
Breathe in, tighten the external oblique on the far side of the floor, exhale, and then as you breathe in, the external oblique slowly relaxes and the body returns to its original Position.

Tips:
Pay attention to the balance problem on both sides and the standard degree of abdominal force.

name: Offset Push-Up
desc:
-Starting Position:
Hands on the ground, shoulder-width apart or slightly wider than shoulder-width apart. Lift one leg and support the ground with the other leg only. Head, torso and legs in a straight line.

-Action:
Keeping your body stable, slowly bend your elbows to lower your body, keeping your elbows close to your body. Pause briefly when the upper arm is nearly parallel to the ground. Push your body upward to return to the starting position.
When performing the movement, always keep your core muscles tight and your back straight, do not collapse or pucker your hips. Keep your neck naturally extended and don't tilt your head up or down excessively.

-Tip:
Inhale as you descend and exhale as you push up.
Stop training when experiencing discomfort.
Adjust the range of descent according to flexibility and personal ability.

name: One Arm Bar Hangs
desc: Grab the bar with one hand on one side while the rest of your body hangs down naturally. Keep your core tight and avoid swaying your body.

name: One Arm Dumbbell Row
desc:
-Starting Position:
Palms and calves of one side are in contact with the bench, while the other foot stands on the floor in a three-point support. Keep your torso close to parallel to the floor and tighten your core to keep your body stable.
Hold a dumbbell in your other hand and lower your arm naturally.

-Action:
With active force from your upper back, pull the dumbbell up along the side of your body, keeping your arm as close to your body as possible. As you pull up, move your elbow back and up, feeling like you're touching an object behind you with your elbow.
When the dumbbells are pulled to a position on either side of the abdomen, hold a short pause and slowly return to the starting position.

-Tip:
Exhale as you pull up and inhale as you lower down.
Stop training when you experience discomfort.
Keep your body stable and don't sway to avoid borrowing strength and to reduce the risk of injury.

name: One Arm Kettlebell Military Press To Th
desc:
Starting Position:
Standing still, grab a kettlebell with your right hand and hold it over your right shoulder, with your feet shoulder-width apart.

Action
Push the kettlebell up and down with your right arm until it is raised above your head, rotating your arm forward in the palm of your hand.After passing overhead, pause briefly and resume the original motion.

Tip:
Pay attention to maintain the rhythm of the exercise to avoid unnecessary injuries.

name: One Arm Kettlebell Swings
desc:
Starting Position:
Stand above the kettlebell with your feet shoulder-width apart.

Action:
Gradually bend your knees slightly and let your right hand drop until you reach the kettlebell handle.Grab the kettlebell with one hand and swing it up between the legs. As the kettlebell swings, the hip legs exert strength, the knees are straight, the roots of the feet hit the ground, tighten the core, and squeeze the hips.As the kettlebell swings downwards, it gradually returns to its original shape.Repeat to recommended times.

Tip:
Pay attention to the rhythm of the exercise, beginners can start with a light weight kettlebell.

name: Open Hand Grip
desc: Please follow your training program for 4-finger hang or 3-finger hang. We generally dont recommend 2-finger hang unless you have specific training goals, to prevent injury. The same rule applies to the depth of the hold as well.

name: Outer Thigh Stretch
desc:
-Starting Position:
Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart, keeping your spine naturally straight and your core tight.

-Action:
Cross one leg in front of the other, with the hand on the same side of the front leg crossed and the opposite hand raised to point to the sky.
Tilt your torso in the direction of the crossed hand and feel the stretch in your outer thigh.

name: Overhead Ball Slam
desc:
Starting Position:
In a standing Position, hold a medicine ball in both hands, knees slightly bent, feet shoulder-width apart.

Action:
Lift your arms up, lift the ball over your head, and hit the ground in front of you.Wait for the ball to bounce, with both hands to catch the ball.

Tips:
The training process emphasizes the training of explosive force.

name: Parallel Bar Dips
desc:
Starting Position:
Grip both bars with your hands and lower yourself until your elbows are at 90 degree angles.

Action:
Lift yourself up by extending your arms until your elbows are close to locking and lower yourself back after a short pause.

Tips:
Breathe out while pushing yourself up and breathe in while lowering yourself down.

name: Pec Deck Flys
desc:
Starting Position:
While sitting on the machine, adjust the seat height so that the handle is at shoulder height and the arms are slightly bent.

Action:
With both hands open and hold the handles on each side, pull the instrument from both sides to the center with chest force, pause briefly and slowly return to the Starting Position.

Tips:
Do not open the arms too far (open to the back of the plane is ok), so as not to hurt the shoulder joint, the weight is not too heavy, adduction pause for 3 seconds, fully squeeze the pectoralis major.

name: Pike Push-Up
desc:
-Starting Position:
Brace your hands on the ground with them wider than shoulder width apart.
Keeping your legs together, lift your hips up so that your body forms an inverted ""V"" shape. Head, torso in a straight line. The center of gravity is located between the hands and feet.

-Action:
Keeping your body stable, slowly bend your elbows and move your head closer to the ground while keeping your body in an inverted ""V"" shape. Pause briefly when the upper arm is nearly parallel to the ground. Push your body upward to return to the starting position.
Keep your core muscles tight and your back straight at all times while executing the movement.

Tip:
Inhale on the way down and exhale on the way up.
Stop training when experiencing discomfort.
Adjust the range of descent according to flexibility and personal ability.

name: Plank Jacks
desc:
Starting Position:
Bend the arm, bend the body, support the ground, keep the back and waist straight, both legs straight, feet together.

Action:
Use lower limb strength to beat the legs apart for about 60, pause briefly to beat again to return to the Starting Position, and repeat until the recommended number of times.

Tips:
Keep your waist and back straight and your arms unbent.

name: Plank Jacks
desc:
-Starting Position:
Bend over for support, arms straight out just below the shoulders, elbows slightly bent, core tight, back straight, legs straight back, toes on the ground.

-Action:
Abdominal power drives the legs to jump forward, knees as close to the chest as possible, while the hips lift slightly.
Immediately after your toes touch the ground, jump backward to the starting position.

Tips:
Exhale as you jump forward and inhale as you jump back.
Keep your core tight the entire time to avoid collapsing at the waist.

name: Plank Row
desc:
-Starting Position:
Arms perpendicular to the floor, dumbbells in hand, shoulder-width apart, palms facing each other. Spread your feet shoulder-width apart. Support your body through the dumbbells and feet, keeping your core tight and ensuring that your head, torso and legs are in a straight line.

-Action:
With active force from one side of the upper back, pull the dumbbells up along the side of the body, keeping the arm as close to the body as possible. As you pull up, move your elbow back and up, feeling like you are touching an object behind you with your elbow.
When the dumbbells are pulled to a position on either side of the abdomen, hold a short pause and slowly return to the starting position.

-Tip:
Exhale as you pull up and inhale as you lower down.
This movement is used to improve core stability, so it's important to coordinate your power through your lower back and hips to prevent your body from twisting or wobbling during the workout.

name: Plank Step Ups
desc:
Starting Position:
Hold the push-up position on the mat and keep your body straight.

Action:
Bend one arm, support the ground with the forearm, then repeat with the other arm, pause briefly and return to the push-up position in the same order.Repeat until recommended number of times.

Tip:
Keep your balance and keep your body straight during the exercise.

name: Plank with Lateral Movement
desc:
-Starting Position:
Arms perpendicular to the ground, palms touching the ground, shoulder-width apart, fingers facing forward. Feet together. Tighten your core to ensure that your head, torso and legs are in a straight line.

-Action:
Step one foot out to one side and move the opposite hand to that side at the same time, completing the pose with arms crossed and legs open.
The other foot comes closer to the stepping foot and the opposite hand moves in the same direction at the same time, completing the actually pose.
Alternate, moving your body in a side-to-side direction.

-Tip:
This movement is used to improve core stability, so it is important to coordinate the force through the waist, abdomen and hips during training to prevent the body from twisting or swaying.

name: Plank with Rotation
desc:
-Starting Position:
Elbows are located directly below the shoulders, with the lower arms parallel to the shoulders. Feet are spread apart, shoulder-width apart. Core tightens to ensure that the head, torso and legs are in a straight line.

-Action:
Turn your body to the side while opening the arm on the same side to point directly overhead. Core tightens to keep head, torso and legs in a straight line.

-Tip:
Exhale as you rotate and inhale as you return.
This movement is used to improve core stability, so it is important to coordinate the force through the lower back and hips to prevent the body from twisting or wobbling as you train.
You can alternate rotations or train on one side only.

name: Planks
desc:
Starting Position:
Lie prone on the floor with forearms supporting the upper body.

Action:
Lift the body off the floor. Squeeze the gluteal muscles. The back should be straight. Your weight should be supported on the forearms and toes only.

Tips:
Ensure your hips are not too low.Keep your body straight.

name: Power Clean
desc:
-Starting Position:
Open your feet shoulder-width apart with your toes facing slightly outward.
Squat down and hold the barbell using a positive grip. Grip your hands slightly wider than shoulder-width apart, with your elbows straight and on the outside of your knees.
Keep your back straight, chest open, head in line with your torso, shoulders above the barbell, and eyes forward.

-Action:
First Pull-Up:
Strongly extend hips and knees, lift the barbell
Keeping the angle of the torso to the floor constant, the barbell bar is pulled upward near the calves.
TRANSITION:
Barbell is pulled to knee height, hips forward, knees slightly bent, thighs over barbell, knees under barbell.
Second Pull-Up:
Quickly extend the hip, knee, and ankle joints with the barbell close to the body.
As the lower leg joints approach full extension, quickly shrug your shoulders upward.
As the shoulders reach their highest position, bend the elbows and continue to pull the barbell upward.
Catch the bar:
Once the barbell reaches its highest point, flip your arms underneath the barbell while bending your knees to a quarter squat position.
Raise your upper arms up as high as you can, close to parallel to the floor. Catch the barbell using the anterior deltoid fascia. Keep your torso straight as you catch the bar.
Once the barbell is stabilized, stand up straight.
Lower:
Lower your elbows, lower the barbell to your thighs, bend your hips and knees, and slowly lower the barbell back to the floor.

Tip:
The movement requires continuous, uninterrupted, explosive force to pull the barbell up through the stirrups and extensions.
The movement is difficult, it is recommended to practice with lighter weights, and gradually increase the weight after the movement is skillful.

name: Power Point
desc:
Starting Position:
Keep your legs together and your arms open in line with your shoulders.

Action:
Use your waist and abdomen to lift your legs high and swing alternately to the sides. Use your hands to keep your balance and swing to the recommended number of times.

Tip:
In the exercise process, pay attention to the body parts of the power, do not rely on the strength outside the waist and abdomen, exercise to maintain the rhythm, to avoid injury.

name: Power Squats
desc:
Starting Position:
Place the barbell on the tip of the trapezius.Chest straight, back and waist straight, head straight ahead.Open your feet, hip width apart, and point your feet outward.

Action:
Bend your knees and lower your body, pushing your hips as far back as possible.Make sure your knees are in line with your feet.Keep your torso as upright as possible.Keep your back straight and continue to lower your body, keeping weight focused on the front of your heels.When the thighs touch the calves, move in the opposite direction, moving the barbell up.

Tips:
Pay attention to the reasonable control of the load during the training to avoid injury.

name: Preacher Curls
desc:
Starting Position:
Place your upper arms against the arm rests and grab the easy-curl-bar with your arms close to being fully extended.

Action:
Raise the easy-curl-bar up until your forearms are perpendicular to the floor and lower it back down after a short pause.

Tips:
Keep your back and upper arms still throughout.

name: Prisoner Calf raise
overview: Hands behind head. One foot on box. Calf raise by pushing foot of floor.

name: Prone A's
desc:
-Starting Position:
Feet apart, shoulder-width apart, lean forward slightly, knees slightly bent, keep your body stable.
Lean forward, torso as parallel to the ground as possible, arms naturally hanging down, palms facing each other, thumbs forward.

-Action:
Raise and open your arms backward, pause briefly at the highest point, and hold your arms in an A-shape.
Slowly return to the starting position.

-Tips:
Exhale as you lift and inhale as you lower.
Stop the exercise if you experience discomfort.

name: Prone Cobra
desc:
-Starting Position:
Lie down on your stomach with your arms straight forward, legs straight, and your whole body relaxed against the floor with your forehead lightly tapping the ground.

-Action:
Simultaneously contract the muscles of the back, buttocks, and legs, lifting the upper body (chest, shoulders, and head), as well as the legs, up and off the ground at the same time. At the same time raise your arms upward as much as possible as well, keeping them straight.
During the movement, keep your neck naturally extended and do not tilt your head up or down excessively.
When the body reaches the highest point, pause briefly for 2 to 3 seconds and slowly return to the starting position.

Tips:
Exhale as you lift and inhale as you lower.

name: Prone Hip Circles
desc:
Starting Position:
Look for a firm support, keep your body leaning forward for support, step back with your feet, stand on one leg, knees bent.

Action:
Maintain a one-legged standing posture, the dangling leg with the hip joint as the axis to rotate from the bottom up, while the supporting leg with the hanging leg and gradually raise, until only the toes of the ground;The dangling leg begins to descend, and the supporting leg then descends until the ball of the foot hits the ground.

Tips:
Keep your balance during rotation and warm up to prevent hip strain.

name: Prone I's
desc:
-Starting Position:
Feet apart, shoulder-width apart, lean forward slightly, knees slightly bent, keep your body stable.
Lean forward, torso as parallel to the ground as possible, arms naturally hanging down, palms facing each other, thumbs forward.

-Action:
Open your hands forward and pause briefly after your arms and torso are in a straight line, with your body in an I-shape.
Slowly return to the starting position.

-Tips:
Exhale as you lift and inhale as you lower.
Stop training if you experience discomfort.

name: Prone T's
desc:
-Starting Position:
Feet apart, shoulder-width apart, lean forward slightly, knees slightly bent, keep your body stable.
Lean forward, torso as parallel to the ground as possible, arms naturally hanging down, palms facing each other, thumbs forward.

-Action:
Raise your arms to the sides, pause briefly after your arms are parallel to the ground, and put your arms in a T-shape with your body.
Slowly return to the starting position.

-Tips:
Exhale as you lift and inhale as you lower.
Stop the exercise if you experience discomfort.

name: Prone W's
desc:
-Starting Position:
Keep your feet apart, shoulder-width apart, and lean slightly forward with your knees slightly bent to keep your body stable.
Lean forward with your torso at a 30 to 45 angle to the floor, bend your elbows, palms facing your body, thumbs facing out.

-Action:
Raise your arms to your sides and pause briefly after your arms reach a W with your body.
Slowly return to starting position.

-Tips:
Exhale as you lift and inhale as you lower.
Stop the exercise if you experience discomfort.

name: Prone Y's
desc:
-Starting Position:
Feet apart, shoulder-width apart, lean forward slightly, knees slightly bent, keep your body stable.
Lean forward, torso as parallel to the ground as possible, arms naturally hanging down, palms facing each other, thumbs forward.

-Action:
Raise and open your hands forward, pause briefly after your arms are in a straight line with your torso, and put your arms in a Y shape with your body.
Slowly return to the starting position.

-Tips:
Exhale as you lift and inhale as you lower.
Stop the exercise if you experience discomfort.

name: Pull-ups
desc:
Starting Position:
Grab the rail with both hands in a wide Position, palms facing forward.

Action:
Pull yourself up with both hands until your chin reaches just above the rail and lower yourself back down after a short pause.

Tips:
Breathe out while raising yourself and breathe in while lowering yourself back.

name: Push-ups
desc:
Starting Position:
Lie prone on the floor, body fully extended, hands in a medium grip Position with only your hands and feet touching the floor.

Action:
Push yourself up by extending your arms and lower yourself back down after a short pause.Repeat to recommended number of times.

Tips:
Breathe out while pushing yourself up and breathe in while lowering yourself down.

name: Quad Stretch with Reach
desc:
-Starting Position:
Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart, keeping your spine naturally straight and your core tight.

-Action:
One hand grasps the ipsilateral ankle and pulls it toward the hip, with the thigh close to the standing leg and the knee pointing toward the floor. Meanwhile the opposite hand points toward the ceiling.
Hold for 1-2 seconds, switch legs and do the stretch on the other side.

-Tip:
This can be practiced in place or alternately while marching.
You can also tiptoe on the toes of the standing leg while stretching to stretch further.

name: Quadriceps Stretch
desc:
-Starting Position:
Front and back legs in a half-kneeling position (front leg bent at about 90 degrees, back leg on the knee). Torso is straight, avoiding excessive forward or backward leaning at the waist.

-Action:
Rear side foot is slowly pulled towards the hip by the opposite hand, push the hips forward, feel the stretch in the front of the thigh, and keep the body balanced.

-Tip:
Don't hold your breath and maintain a breathing rhythm.
Stop training if you experience discomfort.

name: Rainbow Slam
desc:
-Starting Position:
Feet apart, shoulder-width apart, hands on medicine ball.

-Action:
Rotate your waist and shoulders on the axis of your body's midline. Raise the medicine ball above your head and build up the energy for a downward smash.
Lean your torso slightly forward and bend your knees and hips to quickly release the force of the rotation and downward smash.
With the rebounding ball, return to the starting position and smash again in the opposite direction.

Tip:
Pay attention to the consistency of the movement.
Explosive strength training requires a quick release of force from all parts of the body.

name: Reverse Curl
desc:
-Starting Position:
Feet apart, shoulder-width apart, body slightly leaning forward, knees slightly bent, keep the body stable.
Hold a dumbbell in each hand, arms hanging down naturally, dumbbells located at the sides of the body, palms facing back.

-Action:
Keeping your upper arms stationary and using your elbows as a pivot point, bend the dumbbells upward along the sides of your body. The wrist direction remains the same and the dumbbells track as close to the body as possible. Pause briefly after reaching the maximum amplitude and slowly return to the starting position.

-Tip:
Exhale on the way up and inhale on the way down.
Stop training if you experience discomfort.
Stabilize your body and don't sway, avoid borrowing force from your lower extremities.

name: Reverse Flys With Bands
desc:
Starting Position:
Keep your stance facing one side of the gantry and tie the elastic band to the side of the gantry to leave the same length.

Action:
Pull the elastic band on each side of your hands and tighten the band against your chest, keeping your arms straight.Use chest strength to pull the elastic band to the sides of the body to do chest expansion exercise.

Tips:
Keep the movement slow to ensure the effectiveness of the movement.

name: Reverse Grip Tricep Pushdown
desc:
Starting Position:
Stand with feet, knees slightly bent, chest out, belly in, waist straight, body slightly forward, upper arm clamp ribs and remain motionless.

Action:
Hold the base of the rope in both hands, palms up, and slowly press down until the arms are nearly straight.Pause briefly and tighten for 1-2 seconds. Return slowly.

Tips:
You can't stretch by body gravity, you just move your forearms.

name: Reverse Hack Squat
desc:
-Starting Position:
Facing the Hacker, stand on the pedals with your feet shoulder-width apart or slightly wider and your toes facing slightly outward, about 15 degrees or so. Keep your body straight and shoulder carry the side cushions. Hold the handles with both hands to keep your body stable.

-Action:
Squat down with your knees pointing in the direction of your toes. Squat down until your thighs are parallel to the pedals and then pause slightly.
Extend the hip and knee joints and slowly return to the starting position.

-Tip:
Inhale as you squat and exhale as you rise.
Tighten your core to prevent spinal injuries.
You can change directions and lean back to train.
Stop training if you feel discomfort during the movement.

name: Reverse Lunge
desc:
-Starting Position:
Stand with your feet together.
Keep your back naturally straight and tuck in your stomach and chest. Clasp your arms in front of your chest or cross your arms to maintain your balance.

-Actions:
Take a large step backward with one foot on one side, landing on your toes, dropping your hips, and squatting, with the knee of the front leg oriented in the same direction as the toes.
Squat down until the thigh of the front leg is parallel to the ground and slowly return to the starting position.

-Tip:
Inhale as you squat and exhale as you rise.
Stop training when you experience discomfort.
Tighten your core the entire time to avoid swaying your body.
You can carry a barbell on your back or hold a dumbbell kettlebell for weight training.

name: Reverse Step-Down
desc:
-Starting Position:
Stand on a step or platform at the right height with your hands used for balance.

-Actions:
Lift one foot backward, hanging off the ground, and support your body weight with the other foot. Bend the hip and knee on the supporting side and slowly approach the ground with the raised foot. Once the foot is close to the ground or nudges the ground, extend the supporting leg and return to the starting position.

-Tip:
Adjust the height of the step to adjust the difficulty of the movement.
Tighten your core and lift or open your hands to keep your balance and movement stable.

name: Reverse Wrist Curls
desc:
Starting Position:
In a sitting Position, hold the barbell with your wrists against your knees and palms facing up.

Action:
Bend your wrists to lift the barbell and lower it slowly after a brief pause.

Tips:
Always press your forearm against your thigh.

name: Romanian Deadlift
desc:
-Starting Position:
Standing with feet shoulder-width apart, knees slightly bent, barbell resting against the front of the thighs, torso straight. Hands are held squarely in a shoulder-width grip.

-Action:
Push back at the hips and lower the barbell along the front of the thighs to just below the knee (without touching the floor), feeling the hamstring stretch and keeping the barbell close to the body.
Glutes and hamstrings fire as hips push forward back to starting position, tightening glutes.

-Tip:
Exhale on the pull up and inhale on the lower down.
Core tightens to avoid bending the back.
Forward and reverse grips (one hand forward and one hand backward) may be used to enhance stability.

name: Run Lunges
desc:
Starting Position:
Stand up and get your body ready to run.

Action:
Kick your body out, bend your other knee and lunge forward. When you land, lunge legs will continue to lunge your body forward. Repeat until the recommended number of times.The arm swings in rhythm.

Tip:
Pay attention to the power position and maintain the air position.

name: Running Butt Kicks
desc:
Starting Position:
Maintain a standing position.

Action:
Try and quickly kick your butt with your heel as your calf comes up. Push your body forward with the supporting leg. 

Tip:
Maintain your balance and pace during workout.

name: Running In Place
desc:
Starting Position:
Maintain a standing posture and prepare yourself to run.

Action:
Run on the spot at a fast pace with your arms swinging naturally. 

Tip:
Maintain your balance during workout.

name: Running With High Knees
desc:
Starting Position:
Maintain a standing position.

Action:
Lift up your left knee to your chest. Switch to lift your right knee to your chest. Continue the movement, alternating legs and moving at a running pace.

Tip:
Consistent rhythym in tune with consistent breathing will help to mazimize the effect of this exercise.

name: Running With High Knees (Faster Pace)
desc:
Starting Position:
Maintain a standing position.

Action:
Lift up your left knee to your chest. Switch to lift your right knee to your chest. Continue the movement, alternating legs and moving at a sprinting pace.

Tip:
Consistent rhythym in tune with consistent breathing will help to mazimize the effect of this exercise.

name: Russian Twist Med Ball Slam
desc:
-Starting Position:
Sit on the floor or workout mat with your legs slightly bent and your upper body upright. Bend your arms slightly and hold the medicine ball with both hands in front of your abs.

-Action:
Slowly lift your legs off the floor and rotate your abdominal muscles to move the medicine ball to the side of your body and slam it into the floor, rebound and catch the medicine ball, then rotate your abs to the starting position. Then perform the movement to the other side.

-Tips:
Pay attention to control the speed during the rotation, violent rotation will hurt your back, and your feet should not touch the ground.

name: Russian Twists
desc:
Starting Position:
Sit on the floor or on a mat with your legs slightly bent and upper body erect. Bend your arms slightly and hold the bar in front of your abs with both hands.

Action:
With legs elevated off the floor rotate the weight around your abs letting the weight slightly touch the floor next to you. Keep rotating the weight side to side while engaging your core.

Tip:
In the process of rotation, pay attention to control the speed as violent rotation could hurt your back.

name: Saw Plank
desc:
-Starting Position:
Hands on the ground, shoulder-width or slightly wider. Feet apart, shoulder-width apart. Support your body through your elbows and feet with your core tightened to ensure that your head, torso and legs are in a straight line.

-Action:
Move your body rhythmically back and forth using your elbows as an axis.

-Tip:
This action is used to improve core stability, so it's important to coordinate your power through your lower back and hips to prevent your body from twisting or wobbling during the workout.

name: Scapular Pull-Up
desc:
-Starting Position:
Hold the bar squarely in both hands with a grip slightly wider than shoulder width and palms facing forward. The body hangs naturally, the feet may be crossed or bent at the knees, and the core is tightened to avoid body sway.

-Action:
Keeping your elbows unbent, contract the muscles in your upper back and pull your shoulder blades downward. Move up a short distance and pause at the highest point.

-Tip:
Exhale as you pull up and inhale as you lower down.

name: Seated Cable Row
desc:
Starting Position:
Keep seated on the instrument, step on the pedals in front of you, bend your knees slightly, hold the triangle handle in both hands, extend your arms forward, keep your waist and abdomen fixed, and raise your chest.
start
Use the strength of your back muscles to pull the handle to your abdomen, pulling your shoulders and elbows as far back as possible until the handle touches your midsection.Control reduction with latissimus dorsi muscle strength after a brief stay.

Tips:
Keep your elbows close to your rib cage and control your speed.

name: Seated Calf Raise
desc:
-Starting Position:
Sit in a seated position with the forefoot of your feet resting on a barbell piece or step, at a height from the floor.
Hands secure the weights above the knees.

-Action:
Power up the back of your calves and lift your heels upward. Pause briefly when the heel is raised to the highest point. Lower your body until your heels are below the height of the pedals and you feel a stretch in the back of your calves.

-Tip:
Exhale as you lift and inhale as you lower.
Stop the workout if you experience discomfort.
Movements can be performed unassisted to reduce difficulty.

name: Seated Dumbbell Concentration Curls
desc:
Starting Position:
Sit sideways on a bench, rest one arm against your thigh and hold a dumbbell with that hand down between your legs, palm facing the other leg.

Action:
Raise the dumbbell towards your shoulder and slowly lower it back down after a short pause. Alternate after a set.

Tips:
