Keep your back and upper arms still throughout.

name: Seated Dumbbell Press
desc:
Starting Position:
Sit down and hold two dumbbells just above your shoulders, palms facing each other, knees arched.

Action:
Push the dumbbells straight up until your arms are close to locking and lower them back down slowly after a short pause.

Tips:
Breathe out while pushing up and breathe in while lowering back.

name: Seated Dumbbell Triceps Extensions
desc:
Starting Position:
Keep sitting down and hold one dumbbell with both hands behind your head, upper arms pointing straight up, elbows at 90 degree angles.

Action:
Raise the dumbbell by straightening your arms and slowly lower it back after a short pause.

Tips:
Keep your upper arms still throughout.

name: Seated Front Press
desc:
Starting Position:
Sit down and hold barbell just above your shoulders, palms facing each other, knees arched.

Action:
Push the dumbbells straight up until your arms are close to locking and lower them back down slowly after a short pause.

Tips:
Breathe out while pushing up and breathe in while lowering back.

name: Seated Head Harness Neck Resistance
desc:
Starting Position:
Sit in a chair with your feet slightly wider than your shoulders with your toes pointing out. Combine the appropriate collar and bell piece. Lean forward until it is almost parallel to the ground, tying the collar to the head. Hold the bell with both hands and lift your body up until it is almost perpendicular to the ground. Then place your hands on your knees and lean your head and body forward slightly.

Action
Slowly lower your head until your chin touches your chest and inhale. Exhale, raise your head and return to the starting position.

Tips:
The range of movements is slow and rhythmic. TBe careful with adding weight as to endure your safety.

name: Seated Lat Pulldowns
desc:
Starting Position:
Hold a D - shaped handle or straight grip and attach it to a high pulley.Stand 40 to 50 cm away from the puller.Keep your feet spaced out, toes pointing out, knees slightly bent.Keep your feet firmly on the spot, hold the bar in both hands, and slowly turn, keeping your stomach and back straight and under pressure.

Action:
Pull the handle from the Starting Position to the Position of the other foot with both arms. After a short stay, slowly return to the Starting Position.

Tips:
In the process of restoring the Starting Position, it is necessary to maintain a certain speed with the strength of both arms.

name: Seated Leg Raise
desc:
Starting Position:
Sit on the bench with your hands behind your hips, palms down.

Action:
Use lumbar abdomen force to bend knee, at the same time double leg merges raise till heel is close to hip, after stopping for a short time slow restore original state, during both feet cannot touch the ground.

Tips:
Keep your balance and work slowly and efficiently.

name: Seated Resistance Band Tibialis Raise
desc:
-Starting position:
Fix the elastic band at a height close to the floor.
In a seated position, with the leg on the training side straight and toes forward, hang the elastic band over the instep, maintaining some tension. The other side leg bends at the knee to support the ground, and the hip, and the hands to maintain the stability of the body.

-Actions:
Power the front of your calf to hook your toes back until maximum amplitude. Slowly return to the starting position.

-Cue:
Exhale as you hook back and inhale as you return.
Stop training if you experience discomfort.
Adjust the amount of resistance according to the elasticity of different elastic bands.

name: Seated Scissor Kicks
desc:
Starting Position:
Maintain a 45 degree sitting position on the mat with your hips on the floor, hands flat at your sides for balance, legs off the floor, knees slightly bent.

Action:
Lower one leg toward the floor as you lift the other leg up. This is the start of the scissoring motion. Continue the scissoring motion by slowly switching your legs up and down for the recommended amount of repetitions.

Tip:
Keep your balance during the exercise and keep all parts of your body off the ground except your hips and arms.

name: Short Stride Running
desc:
Starting Position:
Maintain a standing posture and prepare yourself for running

Action:
Run forward with short stride at a fast pace and swing arms accordingly.

Tip:
Maintain the fast pace longer for better training result.

name: Shoulder Press-Machine
desc:
-Starting Position:
Sit in a seated position, maintaining postural stability through foot, hip, and back contact with the apparatus. Grasp the handles of the apparatus with both hands, with the lower arms close to perpendicular to the floor.

-Actions:
With a shoulder strike, extend the elbow to push the handle upward. Pause briefly as the arms straighten.
Control your speed and slowly return to the starting position.

-Tip:
Exhale on the upward push and exhale on the return.
Keep your forearms close to vertical to the ground during the exercise.
Stop training if you feel discomfort during the movement.

name: Shoulder Stretch
desc:
-Action:
Standing or sitting, keep your body stable.
Bring one arm across your chest as close to the opposite shoulder as possible. Then press the other arm longitudinally against the lateral arm and forcefully push it toward your body to increase the stretch. At this point, a noticeable stretch will be felt in the shoulder of the inside arm. Stay at the maximum size for a short period of time.
After completing one side of the stretch exchange the opposite arm for the stretch.

-Tip:
If you feel pain or discomfort during the stretch, stop the movement immediately.
Adjust the magnitude of the stretch according to flexibility and tolerance level.

name: Side Plank
desc:
Starting Position:
Lie on your side on a yoga mat with your elbows on the near side of your body, keeping your body straight.

Action:
Lie on your side with your hips high off the floor and prop your upper body up on your elbow. Hold for as long as directed. 

Tip:
Improve the quality of movement, do not shake the body.

name: Side Plank Knee To Chest
desc:
Starting Position:
Lie on your side and keep your body straight with only your lower arms and feet touching the ground.

Action:
Bring your far leg and arm up simultaneously to a running position and breifly hold until returning to the starting position.  

Tip:
Improve the quality of your movements by keeping your body balanced during practice.

name: Side Plank with Leg Raise
desc:
-Starting Position:
In a sideways support position, touch one foot and forearm to the ground, and tighten your core so that your body is in a straight line.

-Action:
Alternate high leg lifts in a sideways supported position. Lift the leg in a direction parallel to the torso.

-Tips:
Pay attention to tightening the core and maintaining body stability while performing the movement to avoid body swaying and movement distortion.

name: Single Arm Lat Pulldown
desc:
-Starting Position:
Sitting on a stool or kneeling on one leg, keep your back straight, tighten your abdominals, lift your chest and head up, and lean your body back slightly at an angle of about 30-45 from the floor to stabilize your body and provide support for the movement. Hold the rope handle in one hand with the arm straight and the handle on the side of the head with the palm facing inwards.

-Action:
With your back firing, drive your arm to pull the rope down along the side of your body, imagining touching your elbow to your waist, keeping your elbow stable during the pull down and not overly abducted or adducted.
Pull the handle down to shoulder height, and after a brief pause at the lowest point, slowly and in a controlled manner, extend the arm upward to return to the starting position.

-Tip:
Exhale on the pull down and inhale on the return.
The trunk needs to be stable while performing unilateral exercises to reduce the risk of injury.
Choose the right weight.

name: Single Arm Overhead Farmers Walk
desc:
-Starting Position:
Feet apart, shoulder-width apart or slightly narrower, back straight, core tight. Raise the weight above your shoulders with one hand, while the other hand grips the weight naturally down the side of your torso.

-Action:
Slowly march forward in small steps.
Keep your back straight, shoulders open, shoulder blades down, head up, and spine in a neutral position as you move.

-Tips:
Stop the workout when you experience discomfort.
Tighten your core throughout to avoid body sway.

name: Single Arm Scap Pulls
desc:
-Starting Position:
Hold the bar squarely in both hands with a grip slightly wider than shoulder width and palms facing forward. Let go of one hand and drop your body naturally; your feet can be crossed or bent at the knees and your core tightened to avoid body sway.

-Action:
Keeping your elbows unbent, contract the muscles in your upper back and pull your shoulder blades downward. Move up a short distance and pause at the highest point.

-Tip:
Exhale as you pull up and inhale as you lower down.

name: Single Leg Bridge
desc:
Starting Position:
Hold your back and use the strength of your arms and legs to lift your body and keep it arched.

Action:
Lift your legs above your head using the strength of your lower back and abdomen, hold the position slightly and slowly return to your original position.

Tip:
Pay attention to the process of restoring the original should use abdominal strength to slow the body down.

name: Single Leg Curl
desc:
-Starting Position:
Lie on your back with the foot of your training leg on the Swiss ball and the other leg lifted at the knee. Using the shoulders, head and arms as a pivot point, the core and hips are used to lift the body so that the shoulders, hips and legs are in a straight line.

-Action:
Power the back of the thigh of the training leg and bend the knee to pull the Swiss ball toward the hip until the calf is perpendicular to the thigh. Keep the thigh in a straight line with the torso at all times during the training leg's knee flexion, with the other leg in the same position.
Slowly extend the knee back to the starting position.

Tip:
You can reduce the difficulty of the exercise by placing both legs on the Swiss ball at the same time.
Instead of a Swiss ball, a sliding disk can be used, with similar movements and results.
Exhale when you bend your knee and inhale when you extend it.

name: Single Leg Deadlift
desc:
Starting Position:
Support yourself on one leg with your knees slightly bent, your upper body forward parallel to the ground, and your other leg straight back to keep your body flat.

Action:
With a soft bend in the standing knee, extend one leg out behind you, hinging at the hips. Tipping your torso forward, until its almost parallel to the floor. Then rise back to a standing position to complete one rep.

Tip:
Pay attention to your balance during the exercise.

name: Single Leg Shoulder Press
desc:
-Starting Position:
Stand on one leg, keeping your body balanced.
Hold dumbbells in ipsilateral or contralateral hand with elbows flexed at 90 degrees and dumbbells on either side of shoulders.

-Action:
With your core tightened, push the dumbbells vertically upwards above your head with your arms close to straight, avoiding locking your elbows.
Slowly lower the dumbbells to the starting position.

-Tip:
Maintain balance during the exercise and avoid swinging significantly.
You can hold the dumbbells in both hands at the same time for the exercise or alternate.

name: Single Leg Squats
desc:
Starting Position:
Maintain a standing posture, arms naturally droop, upper body remain straight.

Action:
Gently lift one leg off the ground with force from the hip. Slowly bend the knee of the supporting leg to squat down. Keep the leg straight and reach out to the front of the body. Slowly open the arms to keep the body balanced.

Tip:
Pay attention to maintain the balance of the body, beginners can use the bench as an aid, squat down to sit on the bench, stand up from the bench on the beginning.

name: Single-Leg Calf Raise
desc:
-Starting Position:
The forefoot of one foot is on the edge of the pedal or step, and the other foot hangs in the air.
Keep your body straight, stomach and chest tucked in, head straight, and eyes flat in front of you. One hand gently holds on to a wall or other fixed object to help maintain balance, avoiding borrowing force during the movement. Avoid borrowing force during the movement. Bear weight in the other hand.

-Action:
Raise your heels as high as you can, letting your toes bear the full weight of your body, and lift your body upward quickly. During the heel lift, keep your body stable and do not sway or lean.
When the heel is raised to the highest point, pause briefly. Lower your body until your heels are below the height of the pedals and you feel a stretch in the back of your calves.

-Tip:
Exhale on the way up and inhale on the way down.
Stop the workout if you experience discomfort.
Movements can be performed unassisted to reduce difficulty.

name: Single-Leg High Knee Jump
desc:
-Starting Position:
Stand with one foot on a stool behind you.

-Action:
Bend the knee of the standing leg and bring the body down until the thigh is nearly parallel to the ground. Then quickly push your foot into the ground and extend, jumping upward with all your strength, your thighs following as far up as they can go. Land with your front foot and cushion your hips and legs.

Tips:
Exhale as you build up strength for the jump and inhale as you cushion the fall.
Stop training when you experience discomfort.
Weights can be used to increase the intensity of the movement.

name: Single-Leg Hip Bridge
desc:
-Starting Position:
Lie on your back with your legs bent, heels on the floor, and feet shoulder-width or slightly wider apart. Lift one leg.

-Action:
Using the supporting leg, slowly lift your hips upward so that your body forms a straight line from shoulder to knee.
When the hips are raised to the highest point, pause briefly and return to the starting position. The lifted leg does not actively exert force during the movement and maintains the same position.

-Tip:
Focus your attention on glute power with no active force from your hands and feet.
The core is tightened to avoid body swaying or movement distortion.
Exhale to lift the body and inhale to lower slowly.

name: Single-Leg Hops
desc:
-Starting Position:
Choose one leg as the starting leg and slightly bend the other leg for balance.
Keep your body upright, lean your back slightly forward, and swing your arms naturally down or slightly back to build up strength.

Action:
The jumping leg is stomped quickly while the swinging leg is swung forward and upward, along with the arms swinging forward and upward to increase the height in the air.
The aerial position keeps the body extended and the core tight to maintain balance.
The aerial posture can be adjusted by swinging the arms and legs to minimize resistance. The swing leg swings back.
The jumping leg touches the ground on its toes, cushions itself by bending the knee, and jumps again with the force of the swinging leg swinging forward again and the active force of the jumping leg.

name: Sit-ups
desc:
Starting Position:
Lie down on the bench, knees at 90 degree angles, feet stabilized by the foot pads and place your hands behind your ears.

Action:
Roll your upper body up until your elbows touch your knees (or close to it) and lower yourself back down after a short pause.

Tips:
To avoid pulling your neck with your hands, look straight up instead of looking at your knees.

name: Ski Step
desc:
Starting Position:
Stand still and let your arms drop.

Action:
Take a small step with your left foot to the left. Bend your knee and waist to try to touch your left foot with your right hand.After a short pause, return to the original, continue to the right side of the same action, repeat the action to the recommended number of times.

Tip:
Pay attention to the control of body movement rhythm, improve the efficiency of movement.

name: Skipping Rope
desc:
Starting Position:
Hold the jump rope with both hands in a standing Position.

Action:
Shake both hands in one direction and jump with both legs.Repeat until scheduled.

Tips:
Keep your body in rhythm and balance.

name: Slope Hang
desc: Please follow your training program for 4-finger hang or 3-finger hang. We generally dont recommend 2-finger hang unless you have specific training goals, to prevent injury. The same rule applies to the depth of the hold as well.

name: Smith Machine Reverse Kickbacks
desc:
-Starting Position:
Lie prone on a bench with your arms wrapped around the bench to maintain body stability.
With calves and thighs perpendicular and legs open, support the barbell bar with the balls of your feet.

-Action:
Contract your hips and power up to push the barbell bar upward. Pause briefly after reaching maximum amplitude.
Power up to control your speed and slowly return to the starting position.

-Tip:
Exhale on the upward thrust and exhale on the return.
Control the range of motion and weight to reduce the risk of injury.
Stop training if you feel discomfort during the movement.

name: Smith Machine Shoulder Press
desc:
-Starting position:
Adjust the chair back angle to tilt back 15 to 30. Sit in a seated position, maintaining postural stability through foot, hip, and back contact with the chair. Choose an appropriate grip distance with the small arms near perpendicular to the floor and the bar held with the palms facing forward. The height of the barbell bar is close to chin height.

-Action:
Power up to push the barbell bar upward. Pause briefly with arms straight.
Power up to control speed and slowly return to the starting position.

-Tip:
Exhale on the upward push and exhale on the return.
You can choose to train in a standing position, adjusting the height of the barbell bar, feet apart, shoulder-width apart, keeping your body stable and your upper body movement points consistent.
Stop training when you feel uncomfortable during the movement.

name: Smith Machine Squat
desc:
-Starting Position:
Select the height of the barbell bar based on your height. Place the barbell bar on the obliques, feet apart, slightly wider than shoulder width, positioned in front of the plane of the barbell bar, with your body slightly back.

-Action:
Squat down with your knees pointing in the direction of your toes. Squat down until thighs are parallel to the floor and then pause slightly.
Extend the hip and knee joints and slowly return to the starting position.

-Tip:
Inhale as you squat and exhale as you rise.
Tighten your core to prevent spinal injuries.
Stop training if you feel discomfort during the movement.

name: Snatches
desc:
Starting Position:
Stand above the kettlebell with your feet shoulder-width apart.

Action:
Gradually bend your knees slightly and let your right hand drop until you reach the kettlebell handle.The right hand forcefully throws the kettlebell from the middle of the legs to the back of the body, explosively contract the buttocks and leg muscles, and forcefully pushes the heel off the ground to stand the body in a straight line. At the same time, bending the right elbow, pull the kettlebell toward the body, making the kettlebell moving track close to the body.When the kettlebell swings to the height of the head, the right hand quickly passes through the kettlebell handle, connects the kettlebell to the forearm of the right hand, and maintains the kettlebell to the top support position, maintaining the neutral position of the wrist.
When falling, push the kettlebell with a little force with your finger, then hook the kettlebell with your finger and swing it down, then return to the original position, repeat the action until recommended times.

Tip:
Keep the rhythm and keep your back straight and unbent.

name: Soleus raise
overview: Face a wall for balance. Feet shoulder width apart. Bend at knees slightly. Push up from toes to raise heels of the ground. Lower slowly.

name: Split Bench Squat
desc:
Starting Position:
Stand still with one leg resting on a bench in the back.

Action:
Bend your upright legs and knees so that your body sinks until your knees are bent to 90. Pause briefly and use your leg strength to recover.

Tip:
In the process of the leg squat can be appropriately increased weight, improve the training effect.

name: Spring With Lunge Quick Punch
desc:
Starting Position:
Keep lunge posture in lower limbs, stabilize center of gravity, keep upper limbs in combat preparation posture, hold elastic band with one arm, and keep body back to elastic band fixed point.

Action:
Punch forward with one arm repeatedly. Reduce shaking in the rest of the body. Repeat to the recommended number of times.

Tip:
Steady lunge, center of gravity forward pressure, rhythmic and high speed to complete a continuous punch.

Practical Application:
With action one, complete upper limb push-pull combination training, reasonable movement collocation, saving time and high efficiency.

name: Squat Jumps
desc:
Starting Position:
Maintain a squat Position with your back straight, your thighs parallel to the floor, your hands at rest according to your habit, and tighten your hips.

Action:
Use the strength of the lower limbs to bounce, at the same time the body in the air, landing is to restore the Starting Position, a short stay can start the second bounce.

Tips:
Keep your back and waist straight at all times and your thighs parallel to the ground when you land.

name: Squats
desc:
Starting Position:
Feet with shoulder width, toes slightly to the outside, the upper body of the chest and stomach, arms naturally hang.

Action:
The upper body gradually sinks, the buttocks move backward, the use of thigh force to control the slow progress, until the thigh and the ground parallel, the use of thigh force after a short stay on the upper body to restore the Starting Position.

Tips:
During squats, use lower body strength to maintain balance and a steady rhythm of movement, keeping the back straight.

name: Standing Cable Crossover
desc:
Starting Position:
Stand in the center of the cable station gripping each cable (set at the same height on each side)

Action:
While engaging your chest, slowly cross each cable in front and around your torso ending with both handles in front of your chest. Hold for a second and slowly return to the start position. 

Tips:
Both arms require simultaneous power. Lighter weight in the beginning will allow you to understand how to fully engage the chest muscles, maximizing this exercise.

name: Standing Calf Raises
desc:
Starting Position:
Stand up, place the front of your feet on top of a small step and hold a barbell on top of your shoulders behind your neck.

Action:
Raise yourself by standing on your toes and slowly lower yourself back down after a short pause.

Tips:
Make sure that only the calf muscles are exercising.

name: Standing Forward Bend
desc:
-Starting Position:
Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart, keep your body upright and your hands hanging naturally at the side of your body.

-Action:
Keep your legs straight (slightly bent at the knees for hamstring tightness), hands close to the toes, and stomach to the thighs.
Reach maximum amplitude and hold for a while or move up and down in small increments to feel the stretch in your lower back and the back of your gluteals and hamstrings.

-Tip:
Adjust the range of motion based on flexibility; less flexible can increase the spacing between feet.

name: Standing Hamstring Curl
desc:
-Starting Position:
Standing with feet shoulder-width apart, keep your body upright, hands hanging naturally at the side of your body or holding onto a wall/chair for balance.

-Actions:
Slowly hook your toes upwards, trying to form an angle between the instep and the calf, keeping the knee straight.
Return to the starting position and repeat the exercise.

-Tips:
Adjust the range of motion according to the ankle mobility and stop the exercise if there is any discomfort.

name: Standing Knee-to-Elbow
desc:
-Starting Position:
Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart, back straight, and hands by your ears or holding your head.

-Action:
Lift one knee while firing from the abdomen, twisting the torso and touching the knee with the opposite elbow.
Raise the knee as high as you can to hip height.

-Tip:
Exhale as you touch and inhale as you return.
Adjust the range of motion based on flexibility.

name: Standing Leg Raise
desc:
-Starting Position:
Standing with legs together, place elastic loops over the insteps of your feet. Cross your arms or drop them naturally and tighten your core to keep your body stable.

-Action:
Lift the knee of one side leg until the thigh is parallel to the floor, then slowly return to the starting position.
Maintain balance by crossing your arms or coordinating a back and forth swing.

-Tips:
Exhale as you lift your leg and inhale as you return.
Stop training when you experience discomfort.
Adjust the amount of resistance according to the elasticity of different elastic bands.

name: Standing Overhead Ball Throw
desc:
Starting Position:
Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart and hold an exercise ball in your hands.

Action:
Hold the ball behind your head, bend your knees slightly and lean back.Hurl the ball forward, bend your hips, and do this with all your strength.

Tips:
The ball can be thrown at your partner or you can face the wall and use the bounce to do exercises.

name: Standing Side Leg Raises
desc:
Starting Position:
Keep your body in a standing Position with your back and waist straight, feet together, hands akimbo.

Action:
Lift one leg from the side to the top, keeping the knee straight, and pause briefly to slowly return to the Starting Position.

Tips:
The supporting legs should be straight and perpendicular to the ground, keeping the balance of the body and holding the handrails with both hands if necessary.

name: Step Up Jumps
desc:
Starting Position:
Keep the upper body upright and step on the steps about 20cm high.

Action:
Quickly step up the steps and jump up, then switch legs on the way down.Want to rise up, the body is upright, the minimum support time.

Tips:
Can carry on the bare hand or the negative light apparatus training.

name: Step-Ups
desc:
-Starting Position:
Use your obliques to back the barbell up, standing with one foot on a step or platform, with your back foot in a straight line with your body.
Tighten your core to keep your body stable.

-Action:
Power the front side leg to bring the body up the step, with the back side foot either hovering or standing on the step. Control the rate of descent back to the starting position.

-Tip:
Stop training when you experience discomfort.
Dumbbells or kettlebells can be carried in both hands instead of a barbell to provide weight.

name: Stick Warmup 1
desc:
-Starting Position:
Stand with feet shoulder width apart. Grip distance is chosen based on shoulder mobility, and can be increased for less mobility. Arms are straight and hanging down naturally, with the straight stick in front of the body.

-Action:
Keeping your arms straight, slowly lift the straight stick upward from the front of your body, then using your shoulders as an axis, your arms drive the straight stick backward around until it reaches its maximum amplitude.
Once you reach the lowest point, wrap your arms forward to return to the starting position.

Tips:
Inhale as you circle backward and exhale as you circle forward.
Stop the exercise if you experience discomfort.
Keep your arms straight and all other body parts stable during the movement to avoid swaying or rotating.

name: Stick Warmup 2
desc:
-Starting Position:
Stand with feet shoulder width apart. Grip distance is chosen based on shoulder mobility, and can be increased for less mobility. Arms are straight and hanging down naturally, the straight stick is located in front of the body.

-Action:
One arm is raised upward on the axis of the shoulder joint, the upper arm is turned behind the body near the ear, and the other arm hangs down naturally until until it reaches its maximum amplitude.
After reaching the lowest point, the other arm wraps forward, driving the straight stick back to the starting position. Alternate between arms for rotation.

-Tip:
Inhale as you circle backward and exhale as you circle forward.
Stop training when you experience discomfort.
Keep your arms straight and other body parts stable during the movement to avoid swaying or rotating.

name: Stick Warmup 3
desc:
-Starting Position:
Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart. Raise the upper arm forward on one side, bend the lower arm back, palm facing the torso, and hold the upper end of the straight stick, while the other hand holds the lower end of the straight stick. The straight stick is affixed to the large arm, close to parallel with the midline of the torso.

-Action:
The lower hand drives the straight stick upward on the axis of the upper arm until it is at its maximum amplitude. Pause for a short time and return to the starting position.

-Tip:
Stop training in case of discomfort.
Keep other body parts stable during the movement and avoid swaying or rotating.

name: Straight-Arm Pulldown
desc:
-Starting Position:
The pulley of the rope is in the highest position.
Feet apart, shoulder-width apart, lean slightly forward, core tight, back straight. Hold the crossbar in both hands with a slightly wider than shoulder-width grip and palms facing down. Arms are straight and the bar is in front of your face.

-Action:
The latissimus dorsi muscles fire, driving the arms down along the sides of the body in a straight line. Keep your arms straight at all times throughout the downward press.
Press the straight bar close to your thighs. After a short pause, slowly and controllably return your large arms to the starting position.

-Tip:
Exhale as you press down and inhale as you return.

name: Straight-Leg Hops
desc:
-Starting Position:
Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart and your hands hanging naturally.

-Action:
Use your ankle and calf muscles to quickly push your body off the ground, keeping your legs straight and avoiding bending your knees.
Jump with arms swinging naturally to increase jump height and speed.
Land forefoot-first and quickly transition to full feet, keeping the ankle joint stable.

-Tip:
Emphasize quick reaction and flexibility over jump height.
Land with knees slightly bent to cushion the landing to avoid injury.

name: Straight-Leg Run or Bounding
desc:
-Starting Position:
Stand in a standing position with hands hanging naturally.

-Actions:
Keep your knees straight and your toes up, emphasizing quick contact between the forefoot and the ground. Actively pick the ground backward to propel the body forward.
Keep your upper body straight, with your head, shoulders and hips in a straight line and your arms swinging naturally to assist with power.
Swing your arms in a strong and coordinated manner, with your elbows close to the sides of your body and a moderate swing.

Tips:
Reduce the contact time between your feet and the ground, complete the stomping and reaching movements quickly, and keep a brisk pace.

name: Stretch Strap Bicycle On Your Back
desc:
Starting Position:
Lie on your back on your yoga mat with your arms straight over your chest and hold the elastic band tightly.

Action:
Complete the cycle alternately with your legs, and repeat to the recommended number of times.

Tip:
Keep your pelvis tilted back and your lower back pressed to the floor.Maintain 1-2S steady control for better effect.

Practical Application:
It is the best choice for effective core training to mobilize the core muscle group to continuously contract and recruit through the resistance of elastic band and add the dynamic stimulation of cycling movement.

name: Stretch Strap Squat
desc:
Starting Position:
Stand with the elastic strap on the side of your body. Pull the elastic strap with your hands to the standing position and fix the elastic strap.

Action:
Keep the length of the elastic band constant and bend the knees to complete the squat.Repeat the squat to the recommended number of times.

Tip:
Keep your arms straight. Take off and fall at a constant speed.

Practical application:
Improve the anti-rotation ability of the core horizontal plane, which is beneficial to reduce the torso shaking during running and improve running efficiency.

name: Stretch Tape Squat Pull Back
desc:
Starting Position:
Extend one arm forward and hold the elastic band tightly. Let the other arm drop naturally.Keep your knees bent and lower legs in a squat.

Action:
Pull the elastic band towards your body while keeping your upper body straight and slightly leaning back.Both arms swing back and forth naturally, lower limbs from squat movement into standing posture.Return to squat position after a short stay and repeat until recommended times.

Tip:
Squat movement, the center of gravity up and down, rise and fall to be full of flexibility.Maintain a certain rhythm of the movement to improve the training effect.

Practical Application:
Improve muscle strength in lower extremities and reduce the risk of running injuries.

name: Stretch Tape Squats Sideways
desc:
Starting Position:
Hold the half squat position, stand with the body side elastic band, pull the elastic band to the body position with both hands, and fix the elastic band.

Action:
Move the legs laterally in small steps, stretch the elastic band slowly, and repeat until recommended times.

Tip:
Keep your arms straight, your torso steady, your breathing balanced, and your movements smooth.

Practical Application:
In moving march, the control core is close to the core control in actual running.

name: Stretch With Lunge To Lift Knees
desc:
Starting Position:
Keep your upper body straight, extend your left arm in front of you and grip the elastic band, and drop your other arm behind you.Bend your right knee, keep your left leg on your knees, and take a lunge position.

Action:
Pull the elastic band to one side of the body while keeping the upper body straight and slightly tilted back;The arms swing back and forth naturally;At the same time, lunge with your legs straight and kneel with your knees raised.Return to original condition after a short stay and repeat until recommended times.

Tip:
The hands and feet work together, lifting the knee on the tiptoe and exerting steady control at the high point.

Practical Application:
Strengthen the integration of lower limbs and diagonal of the body, which is conducive to improving running efficiency.

name: Sumo Deadlift
desc:
-Starting Position:
Feet are 1.5-2 times shoulder width apart, toes are abducted about 45-60, and knees are oriented in the same direction as the toes.
Hold a barbell in both hands with a shoulder-width or slightly narrower grip, and keep your arms close to your inner thighs.
Hips down, back straight, core tight, shoulder blades aligned with barbell. The calves are close to vertical on the floor and the barbell is close to the shins.

-Action:
With your feet on the ground, push your hips forward and extend your hips to pull up the barbell.
Control your speed on the way down without the barbell touching the floor.

-Cue:
Exhale as you pull up and inhale as you lower down.
Choose foot spacing and range of motion based on flexibility.

name: Sumo Squat
desc:
-Starting Position:
Stand with your feet wide apart, toes facing diagonally forward.
Keep your back naturally straight and tuck in your stomach and chest. Arms are clasped in front of the chest or stretched straight forward to maintain balance.

-Action:
Squat down, bending your knees and hips, with your knees oriented in line with your toes.
Squat down until your thighs are parallel to the floor and slowly return to the starting position.

-Cue:
Inhale as you squat and exhale as you rise.
Stop the workout if you experience discomfort.
Tighten your core the entire time to avoid swaying your body.
You can carry a barbell on your back or hold a dumbbell kettlebell for weight training.

name: Super Push Up
desc:
Starting Position:
Maintain a prone position with legs naturally apart.

Action:
Force the buttocks to raise, lift to cannot lift up so far, use lumbar abdomen force to restore slowly after a short stay as is and homeostatic prop hip, stretch back, maintain after period of time slowly restore prone posture.

Tip:
Pay attention to the body part during the exercise, keep the back straight.

name: Supine Chest Ball Throw
desc:
Starting Position:
Lie on your back on the mat with your knees bent and your feet together. Place the ball on your chest and hold it with your hands.

Action:
Using explosive force, push the ball up as hard as you can along the elbow.When the ball falls, catch it with both hands.

Tips:
More suitable for individual training.

name: Supine Cobra
desc:
-Starting Position:
Lie on your back with your legs straight and together, arms straight above your head and body in a straight line.

-Action:
Using your abdominals, lift your upper body and legs at the same time, touching your toes or calves with your hands as much as possible, forming a ""V"" shape with your body.
Pause at the highest point for 1-2 seconds to feel your abs tighten.
Return to the starting position at a controlled speed, but do not fully relax your limbs and keep them suspended for continued abdominal stimulation.

-Tip:
Exhale on the way up and inhale on the way down.
Stop training if you feel discomfort during the movement.

name: Supine Knee Tucks
desc:
-Starting Position:
Lie on your back with your legs bent at the knees, hands naturally at your sides and arms straight.

-Actions:
Abdominal force, drive the legs towards the chest, reach the maximum amplitude and then pause briefly, slowly return to the starting position.

-Tips:
Exhale as you lift your legs and inhale as you return.

name: Supine Oblique Wood Chop
desc:
-Starting Position:
Lie on your back with your legs bent at the knees, arms crossed above your head and arms straight.

-Actions:
Abdominal force to lift the upper back off the ground, while turning the upper body to the side, and then pressing down on the outside of the thighs on that side with both hands, similar to the ""logging"" action.
After a short pause to return to the starting position, repeat on the other side, alternating between left and right to complete the required number of times.

-Tips:
Exhale when you turn around and inhale when you return.
You can hold a heavy object to increase the difficulty of the movement.

name: Supine Overhead Ball Throw
desc:
Starting Position:
Lie flat on the mat with knees bent and feet together.Hold the ball in one hand and place your arm straight on the ground above your head.

Action:
With abdominal power, lift your upper body in a sit-up motion and throw the ball as far forward as possible.The ball moves into a sitting Position.

Tips:
You can throw the ball to your partner or bounce it off the wall.

name: Supine pull ups
desc:
-Starting Position:
Lie on your back and hold the bar with your hands slightly wider than shoulder width, palms facing forward, and hang your torso from the bar.
Core and lower body power up to ensure head, torso and legs stay in a straight line.

-Action:
Power your upper back and flare out your upper arms, driving your chest closer to the bar.
As the chest approaches the barbell, pause briefly at the top of the movement.
Slowly lower your body back to the starting position.

-Tip:
Exhale on the pull-up and exhale on the return.
Adjust the height of the bar to change the angle of your body to the ground to adjust the difficulty of the movement.
Stop training if you feel discomfort during the movement.

name: T-Bar Rows
desc:
Starting Position:
Secure one end of the bar to a mine rack or corner, and place the bar and a t-shaped handle at the other end.Cross your legs over the bar and hold the t-shaped handle with both hands, arms straight down.Lower hips bent, upper body bent down, back straight, knees slightly bent.

Action:
Using the strength of your back, pull your hands up, contract your shoulders, bend your elbows, draw the barbell up to your chest, and exhale.After a brief pause, return slowly to the Starting Position, inhaling.

Tips:
Pay attention to protect your waist when you are under heavy load and keep the rest of your body still during the exercise.

name: The Elastic Band Bends The Hip And Pres
desc:
Starting Position:
In a semi-squat position, bend your knees slightly, keep your arms straight, one of your arms holding the elastic band, and keep your upper body straight.

Action:
Press down your arms quickly and return to the original position. Pull the elastic band to one side of your body.The hip legs naturally fall and rise with the swing of the arms.Repeat to recommended times.

Tip:
To maintain a fast rhythm, exhale, bend and press the hips down.Adjust your feet and stabilize your center of gravity.

Practical Application:
Large range of motion, conducive to stimulating the heart and lung.Acceleration of hip flexion helps improve centrifugal control. For running touchdown and off-road downhill, buffer control can be greatly improved to reduce the risk of injury caused by impact.

name: The L-sit
desc:
Starting Position:
Sit on a yoga mat with your hands at your sides, palms on the floor, legs together, straight out in front of you.

Action:
Use the strength of your arms and chest to lift your body up and push your hips back, keeping your feet off the ground and your body in the air for the recommended time.Or slowly lower your body and then lift it up with force. Repeat to the recommended number of times.

Tip:
According to the individual actual situation to choose the way of training, in strict accordance with the training requirements, in order to improve the quality of training.

name: Thigh Abductor
desc:
Starting Position:
Sitting in the sitting Position, sit on the thigh abductor and choose the appropriate weight.With your legs in place, squeeze the handle with both hands.The upper body remains stationary.

Action:
Push the machine out with your legs and exhale.Hold for a few seconds as you push to the maximum, then slowly pull your legs back into the Starting Position while inhaling.

Tips:
Keep the upper body still and fixed at all times to avoid pulling.

name: Thigh Adductor
desc:
Starting Position:
Sitting in the sitting Position, sit on the thigh adductor and choose the appropriate weight.With your legs in place, squeeze the handle with both hands.The upper body remains stationary.

Action:
Contract the machine inward with your legs and exhale.Contract until merging and hold for a few seconds, then slowly pull your legs back to the Starting Position while inhaling.

Tips:
Keep the upper body still and fixed at all times to avoid pulling.

name: Thoracic Spine Rotation
desc:
-Starting Position:
Lie on your side with your legs stacked 90 at hip and knee flexion, or one knee pressed against the foam shaft, you need to ensure pelvic stability.
Hands are positioned in front of the chest with arms straight.

-Action:
The outer arm opens back, rotating the thoracic spine backwards, like ""opening a book"", until the arm touches the floor.
Follow the original trajectory back to the starting position.
The head rotates with the arm and the eyes follow the moving hand.

-Tips:
Keep your pelvis and lower extremities stable and avoid lifting your hips or separating your knees.

name: Toe Touch Sweep
desc:
-Starting Position:
Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart, keeping your spine naturally straight and your core tight.

-Action:
Take a small step forward with one foot on one side, hook your toes, straighten your leg, bend at the hip, and feel the stretch in the back of your leg by rowing your hands to the front foot while bending your back leg.
Rise back to a standing position and switch legs for the exercise.

-Tip:
You can practice this in place or alternate as you march.
Exhale as you bend down and inhale as you rise up.
Control the range of motion based on flexibility.

name: Tricep Kickbacks
desc:
Starting Position:
Hold a dumbbell in one hand, with one foot on the floor and the other kneeling on the bench.Keep your upper body bent, parallel to the ground, your back straight, and keep your head up and looking forward.The upper arm on the weight-bearing side is close to the upper body and parallel to the ground, with the forearm down and naturally perpendicular to the ground, and the other arm balanced on a flat bench.

Action:
Holding the upper arm in place, contract the triceps to lift the dumbbell and exhale.Until the arms are fully extended.Pause at the top, then slowly return the dumbbell to its Starting Position, inhaling.

Tips:
Keep everything still except the weight bearing arm.

name: Tricep Stretch
desc:
-Starting Position:
Standing or seated, raise the stretching side arm above your head, bending the elbow, with the palm of the hand near the shoulder blade.

-Action:
With your other hand, pull the elbow of the stretching side toward the midline of your body and feel the three-head stretch.

-Tip:
Keep breathing normally.
Adjust the range according to flexibility to avoid overstretching.

name: Triceps Pushdown-Machine
desc:
-Starting Position:
Sit in a seated position, maintaining postural stability through foot, hip, and back contact with the apparatus. Bend your elbows, keep your arms close to your body, and hold the handles of the apparatus with both hands.

-Action:
With three hairs, extend your elbows to press the handles downward. Pause briefly as arms straighten.
With three hairs force control the speed and slowly return to the starting position.

-Cue:
Exhale as you press down and exhale as you return.
Keep your elbows close to your body throughout the movement.

name: Triceps Pushdowns
desc:
Starting Position:
Stand with feet, knees slightly bent, chest out, belly in, waist straight, body slightly forward, upper arm clamp ribs and remain motionless.

Action:
Hold the base of the rope in both hands, palms down, and slowly press down until the arms are nearly straight.Pause briefly and tighten for 1-2 seconds. Return slowly.

Tips:
You can't stretch by body gravity, you just move your forearms.

name: Trunk Rotations
desc:
Starting Position:
Sit on the floor or on a gym mat with your legs slightly bent and upper body erect.Bend your arms slightly and place the discus in front of your abs with both hands.

Action:
Slowly lift your legs off the floor, roll your abdominal muscles, move the discus to the left side of your body, and let the discus touch the ground.Then move the discus to your right.

Tips:
In the process of rotation, pay attention to control the speed, violent rotation will hurt the back, feet should not touch the ground.

name: TRX Suspended Abdominal Fallout
desc:
Starting Position:
Adjust the suspension rope so that the handle is at the right height and below the waist.Stand up and hold the handle and lean toward the pulley in a push-up Position, keeping the body straight without bending the waist or back.

Action:
Keeping your arms straight, lean further toward the suspended pulley, bringing your body closer to the ground, stretch your shoulders, and raise your arms above your head.When the movement reaches its maximum, pause briefly and slowly return to the Starting Position.

Tips:
Keep your spine neutral and the rest of your body straight. The shoulder is the only joint that moves.

name: TRX Suspended Biceps Curl
desc:
Starting Position:
Adjust the sling to place the handle at chest height.Facing the suspender, reverse grip.Keep your body straight, back and waist not bent, lean back, straight elbows.

Action:
Slowly bend your elbows and pull yourself up, using only your biceps to do this without any other force.At the top of the action, after a short pause, slowly lower yourself to the Starting Position.

Tips:
Note the effectiveness of target muscle group training.

name: TRX Suspended Chest Flys
desc:
Starting Position:
Adjust the practice to a suitable height, the lower the Position, the more difficult the movement.Hold the handle and pull to the front of the body, so that you can rely on the corner of the wall as a support, keeping your body straight, spine naturally bent, arms straight, palms facing each other.

Action:
Start by moving your arms to the sides of your body, away from the midline, and drop your body, which may cause your elbows to bend slightly.When the forearm and trunk are perpendicular, slowly force back to the original Position.

Tips:
Keep your waist and back straight during practice.

name: TRX Suspended Clamp Chest
desc:
Starting Position:
Adjust the handle to the right height.Hold a handle in each hand, palms facing each other.Keep your arms straight and lean back, landing on your heels or the balls of your feet.When doing this movement, different Angle will have different difficulty coefficient.Keep your back, waist and legs straight and your hips tight.

Action:
Extend the shoulders outward, bending the elbows slightly and pulling the body up until the forearms are perpendicular to the body. Slowly combine the arms and straighten them to return to the starting position.

Tip:
Keep the rest of your body straight.

name: TRX Suspended Crunches
desc:
Starting Position:
Adjust the rope so that the handle is at the right height.Position yourself in a push-up Position in front of the suspension, place your feet on the handle, keep your legs straight, hips extended, arms not bent, and back straight.

Action:
Bend your knees and hips, and bend your knees close to your chest.Pause at a controlled high point, then slowly return to the Starting Position.

Tips:
Ensure the same height of the two rope handles during the exercise, and pay attention to your own safety in the process of belly rolling to prevent yourself from injury.

name: TRX Suspended Leg Curl
desc:
Starting Position:
Lie flat on your back in front of the suspension band and adjust to 30 to 46 cm above the ground.Place your feet in the suspension band, press your hands down, palms down, and lift your hips off the floor.Stretch your knees, remember to keep your body straight, and don't bend your back or waist.

Action:
Bend your knees and move your feet toward the gluteus maximus. Slowly rise.Stay where the muscles are most tense, then slowly return to the Starting Position.

Tips:
In the course of the exercise, to ensure that the full force of the exercise muscle, and thereby improve the effectiveness of training.

name: TRX Suspended Split Squat
desc:
Starting Position:
Hang the strap so that the handle is located 45 to 76 cm above the ground.With your back to the rope, place your back foot in the handle behind you.Keep head straight in front, chest straight, back and waist straight, knees slightly bent.

Action:
Gradually bend your knees and hips to lower your body, lowering yourself to the ground.Keep your weight on your heels and maintain good posture during practice.At the bottom of the action, pause briefly and then reverse the motion, stretching the hips and knees to bring the body back to the Starting Position.

Tips:
Keep your body straight as you practice, and keep your body balanced as you squat and rise.

name: Turkish Get Up
desc:
-Starting Position:
Lie on your side with a kettlebell in your near-ground side hand and bent knee.

-Action:
Rotate the body into a supine position and raise the kettlebell upward with one hand, with the same side leg bent at the knee and on the floor; the other hand is held in the same line as the shoulders using a side plank, with both eyes on the kettlebell.
Flat arm elbow support the upper body until the upper body is completely sitting up; switch to palms of the hands to support the ground to raise the body, hip elevation to a certain extent after straightening the leg folded to the back of the body and one-knee kneeling on the ground; the use of kneeling knee and foot power to support the body, the palms of the hands gradually leave the ground, the body to keep straight, folded leg calf adjusted to a comfortable position; legs until the stand up, a short stay in accordance with the reverse order of the restoration of the The same as before.

-Tips:
Pay attention to the balance of the body during the training process, always keep your eyes on the kettlebell, and keep your movements rhythmic and crisp to improve the quality of training.

name: Twist Throw
desc:
-Starting Position:
Stand sideways toward a wall with your feet shoulder-width apart, knees slightly bent, back straight, core tight, and stabilize your weight between your feet.
Hold the medicine ball in both hands and place them on the side away from the wall with your arms naturally bent.

-Actions:
Build Up: Using the center axis of the body as an axis, twist the upper body away from the wall by rotating the waist and shoulders, stretching the muscles to build up strength.
THROW: After twisting the body to its maximum amplitude, quickly utilize the twisting force of the body, the swinging force of the arms, and the force of the leg stomps to slam the medicine ball against the wall. The power should start from the legs and pass through to the waist, shoulders and finally the arms to focus the power on the medicine ball, forming a coherent and explosive power output.
Catch the medicine ball after it bounces and continue to repeat the movement.

-Tip:
Pay attention to the coordination of the joints and the consistency of the movement.

name: Two Arm Kettlebell Swings
desc:
Starting Position:
Keep your front feet crouched directly above the kettlebell.

Action;
Squeeze the hips and legs, grab the kettlebell with both hands and swing it up between the legs. At the top of the kettlebell swing, extend the hip joint, lock the knee, root into the ground, tighten the core and squeeze the hips.

Tip:
Keep the rhythm of the exercise, keep your back straight and avoid shaking.

name: Unilateral Supine Buttocks Lift Hip Lif
desc:
Starting Position:
Lay on your back with your hands by your sides, one foot flat on the floor and knees close together. Bend one knee at a 90-degree angle and keep the other leg straight. 

Action:
Raise your hips as high as possible while keeping the rest of the body still. Slowly return to the starting position.

Tip:
Pay attention to the hips. Do not push with your hands or foot.

name: Upright Leg Raise
desc:
Starting Position:
Lie down on the mat with your back relaxed and your hands at your sides, palms facing down.Keep your upper back firmly pressed to the ground during the exercise.

Action:
Contract your abdomen, lift your legs 90 degrees from your body, and lift your hips slightly until you can no longer lift them, then stop moving and slowly return to your Starting Position.

Tips:
Legs as far as possible to keep straight and stable, control leg movement in the process of movement, do not be affected by inertia.

name: Upright Row
desc:
Starting Position:
Bend forward, grab the barbell with both hands, and slowly lift to regain your standing Position.

Action:
Lift the barbell slowly until it reaches the lower bar height, pause briefly, then resume the Starting Position.

Tips:
Keep your body straight and your speed steady with your arms close to your side.

name: V-Sit Hold
desc:
-Starting Position:
Legs together, knees bent, leg lifted, torso and thighs in a V, upper hips supporting the ground, hands on knees

-Action:
Hands against knees, abdominal force to maintain position

-Tips:
Breathe naturally
Change the duration and the force to adjust the intensity

name: Walking Lunges
desc:
-Starting Position:
Stand in a standing position with your hands naturally down or crossed.

-Action:
Keeping your body stable, take a large step forward with one leg. The front leg lands with the knee bent and the thigh parallel to the ground. Bend the back leg with the thigh perpendicular to the ground and the toes touching the ground.
Rise up, switch legs and step forward until you form a lunge again. Alternate this movement.
Swing your hands naturally or cross your arms for balance during the march.

-Tip:
Maintain balance and avoid swaying while marching.

name: Wall Sit
desc:
Lean your back against a wall and slowly squat down until your calves are perpendicular to the floor and your thighs are parallel to the floor. Maintain this position for some time.
Place your hands on your knees or hang down naturally.

name: Weighted Hanging Leg Raise
desc:
-Starting Position:
Hold the bar in both hands with a grip slightly wider than shoulder-width apart, with your body naturally hanging down, feet together, knees slightly bent, and dumbbells sandwiched between your feet.

-Actions:
Abdominal power drives thighs up, bending the knees in a smooth motion until maximum amplitude.
Slowly return to the starting position.

-Tip:
Stop the workout when you experience discomfort.
You can increase the difficulty of the movement by keeping the legs straight up.

name: Weighted Jump Squats
desc:
-Starting Position:
Stand with your feet shoulder-width apart or slightly wider than shoulder-width apart and your toes facing slightly diagonally forward.
Keep your back naturally straight and tuck in your stomach and chest. Grasp dumbbells with both hands.

-Action:
Squat down, bending your knees and hips, with your knees oriented in the same direction as your toes.
Complete the buildup and then quickly stomp and extend the lower leg to jump upward.
Cushion the landing by slightly bending the knees and hips and return to the starting position.

-Tip:
Stop training if you experience discomfort.
Tighten your core throughout to maintain body stability.
You can use a barbell, or hold other weights in your hands for weight training.

name: Wide Grip Push-Up
desc:
-Starting Position:
Brace your hands on the ground with them wider than shoulder width apart. Head, torso and legs in a straight line.

-Action:
Keeping your body stable, slowly bend your elbows to lower your body. Pause briefly when the upper arm is nearly parallel to the ground. Push your body upward to return to the starting position.
When performing the movement, always keep your core muscles tight and your back straight, without collapsing or puckering your hips. Keep your neck naturally extended and don't tilt your head up or down excessively.

-Tip:
Inhale as you descend and exhale as you push up.
Stop training when experiencing discomfort.
Adjust the range of descent according to flexibility and personal ability.

name: Windshield Wiper
desc:
Starting Position:
Keep your legs together and your arms open in line with your shoulders.

Action:
Use your waist and abdomen to lift your legs high and swing alternately to the sides. Use your hands to keep your balance and swing to the recommended number of times.

Tip:
In the exercise process, pay attention to the body parts of the power, do not rely on the strength outside the waist and abdomen, exercise to maintain the rhythm, to avoid injury.

name: Wrist Curls
desc:
Starting Position:
In a sitting Position, hold the barbell with your wrists against your knees and palms facing down.

Action:
Bend your wrists to lift the barbell and lower it slowly after a brief pause.

Tips:
Always press your forearm against your thigh.

name: Wrist Roller
desc:
-Starting Position:
Hands straight and parallel to the ground, handles in hand, palms facing down.

-Actions:
Alternate wrist forces to roll the handles and rope wraps around to drive the weights upward.

-Tips:
Maintain stability of all body parts except for wrist and small arm force activities.

name: Zercher Squat
desc:
-Starting Position:
Stand with feet shoulder-width apart or slightly wider than shoulder-width apart. Raise both arms back up with elbows bent, securing the barbell through the elbows.
Keep your back naturally straight and tuck in your stomach and chest.

-Action:
Squat down, bending your knees and hips, with your knees oriented in line with your toes.
Squat down until thighs are nearly parallel to the floor, pausing briefly.
Stomp and extend the lower leg to return to the starting position.

-Cue:
Inhale as you squat and exhale as you rise.
Stop training when you experience discomfort.
Tighten your core throughout, keeping your back straight and maintaining body stability.
